{"title_page": "Collins Center for the Arts", "text_new": "{{About|the Collins Center for the Arts at the University of Maine (Orono)|the J. Everett Collins Center in Andover, Massachusetts|J. Everett Collins Center for the Performing Arts}}\nThe '''Collins Center for the Arts''', formerly the '''Maine Center for the Arts''', is a performing arts center and [[concert hall]] located on the campus of the [[University of Maine]] in [[Orono, Maine|Orono]], [[Maine]]. It has been operating since 1986, hosting both local and national artists.<ref>http://bangordailynews.com/2015/07/23/living/performing-arts/collins-center-for-the-arts-announces-30th-anniversary-season/</ref>\n\nThe Center is the home of the [[Bangor Symphony Orchestra]], the oldest continually-operating community orchestra in the US, founded in 1896. The UMaine performing arts groups are also based there. Performers such as [[Garrison Keillor]], [[George Carlin]], and the [[Dave Matthews Band]] have done shows there, and [[Dr. Ruth Westheimer]], Attorney General [[Eric Holder]], and [[Paul Rusesabagina]] have given lectures.\n\nIn August 2007, the University closed the Maine Center for the Arts for an 18-month renovation.  The facility officially re-opened in February 2009, and was renamed the Collins Center for the Arts in honor of donors Richard R. and Anne A. Collins.<ref>https://umaine.edu/news/blog/2007/08/30/umaine-announces-6-million-gift-landmark-facility-to-become-collins-center-for-the-arts/</ref>\n\nThe Center is also home to the [[Hudson Museum]], an anthropology museum with collections of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] and [[South America]]n baskets, weapons and artifacts.<ref>https://bangordailynews.com/2009/10/02/living/lsquotalk-about-transformationrsquo/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of concert halls]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.collinscenterforthearts.com/ Collins Center for the Arts]\n* [http://www.umaine.edu/hudsonmuseum/ Hudson Museum]\n* [http://www.bangorsymphony.com/ The Bangor Symphony Orchestra]\n{{University of Maine}}\n{{coord|44|53|58.75|N|68|39|58.54|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maine culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings at the University of Maine]]\n[[Category:University and college arts centers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Penobscot County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Performing arts centers in Maine]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Maine]]\n\n\n{{Maine-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Collins Center for the Arts at the Univerisity of Maine (Orono)|the J. Everett Collins Center in Andover, Massachusetts|J. Everett Collins Center for the Performing Arts}}\nThe '''Collins Center for the Arts''', formerly the '''Maine Center for the Arts''', is a performing arts center and [[concert hall]] located on the campus of the [[University of Maine]] in [[Orono, Maine|Orono]], [[Maine]]. It has been operating since 1986, hosting both local and national artists.<ref>http://bangordailynews.com/2015/07/23/living/performing-arts/collins-center-for-the-arts-announces-30th-anniversary-season/</ref>\n\nThe Center is the home of the [[Bangor Symphony Orchestra]], the oldest continually-operating community orchestra in the US, founded in 1896. The UMaine performing arts groups are also based there. Performers such as [[Garrison Keillor]], [[George Carlin]], and the [[Dave Matthews Band]] have done shows there, and [[Dr. Ruth Westheimer]], Attorney General [[Eric Holder]], and [[Paul Rusesabagina]] have given lectures.\n\nIn August 2007, the University closed the Maine Center for the Arts for an 18-month renovation.  The facility officially re-opened in February 2009, and was renamed the Collins Center for the Arts in honor of donors Richard R. and Anne A. Collins.<ref>https://umaine.edu/news/blog/2007/08/30/umaine-announces-6-million-gift-landmark-facility-to-become-collins-center-for-the-arts/</ref>\n\nThe Center is also home to the [[Hudson Museum]], an anthropology museum with collections of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] and [[South America]]n baskets, weapons and artifacts.<ref>https://bangordailynews.com/2009/10/02/living/lsquotalk-about-transformationrsquo/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of concert halls]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.collinscenterforthearts.com/ Collins Center for the Arts]\n* [http://www.umaine.edu/hudsonmuseum/ Hudson Museum]\n* [http://www.bangorsymphony.com/ The Bangor Symphony Orchestra]\n{{University of Maine}}\n{{coord|44|53|58.75|N|68|39|58.54|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in the United States]]\n[[Category:Maine culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings at the University of Maine]]\n[[Category:University and college arts centers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Penobscot County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Performing arts centers in Maine]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Maine]]\n\n\n{{Maine-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Univerisity \u2192 University", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collins_Center_for_the_Arts"}
{"title_page": "DHL", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DHL\n| trading_name = \n| logo = [[File:DHL Logo.svg|280px]]\n| type = [[division (business)|Division]]\n| parent = [[Deutsche Post]]\n| foundation = [[San Francisco]], [[California|CA]]<br /> ({{start date and age|1969}})\n| location = [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]\n| key_people = Ken Allen <small>([[Chairman]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/investors/corporate_governance/board_of_management/members/ken_allen.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL - Ken Allen|publisher=}}</ref>\n| founders = <br>Adrian Dalsey <br>Omer Karakus <br>Robert LynnNHNCC,DC';,.D';C.\n| industry = [[Courier|Express logistics]]\n| num_employees = {{increase}} 380,000 (2019)\n| products = DHL Express Worldwide <br> DHL Express 9:00 <br> DHL Express 12:00\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.dhl.com/en.html}}\n}}\n'''DHL (Dalsey, Hillblom and Lynn) International GmbH''' is an American and German courier, parcel, and [[express mail]] service which is a [[division (business)|division]] of the German [[logistics]] company [[Deutsche Post|Deutsche Post DHL]]. Deutsche Post DHL is the world's largest logistics company,<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=https://www.dhl.com/publish/content/g0/en/about/divisions.low.html |title=DHL Divisions |author=DHL/DPAG |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref>  now in over 220 countries and territories worldwide,{{cn|date=September 2019}} particularly in sea and air mail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manager-magazin.de/magazin/artikel/0,2828,708038-4,00.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL: Kunde statt Chaos - manager magazin - Unternehmen|date=22 July 2010|work=manager magazin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gate4logistics.de/logistik-karriere/top-10-unternehmen.html|title=Top 10 Unternehmen|date=12 June 2013|access-date=1 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110081514/http://www.gate4logistics.de/logistik-karriere/top-10-unternehmen.html|archive-date=10 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company delivers over 1.3 billion parcels per year.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.logistics.dhl/global-en/home/about-us.html |title=Company Portrait |website=DHL Company Portrait |access-date=1 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe company was founded in the United States in 1969 and expanded its service throughout the world by the late 1970s. The company was primarily interested in offshore and intercontinental deliveries, but the success of [[FedEx]] prompted their own intra-US expansion starting in 1983.\n\nIn 1998, Deutsche Post began to acquire shares in DHL. It reached controlling interest in 2001, and acquired all outstanding shares by December 2002.<ref name=\"dpdhl.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/about_us/history.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL Group - History|website=www.dpdhl.com}}</ref> The company then absorbed DHL into its Express division, while expanding the use of the DHL brand to other Deutsche Post divisions, business units, and subsidiaries. Today, DHL Express shares its DHL brand with business units such as [[DHL Global Forwarding]] and [[DHL Supply Chain]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/content/dam/dpdhl/Investors/Events/Reporting/2017/FY2016/DPDHL_2016_Annual_Report.pdf |title=2016 Report |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=DPHL |publisher=Deutsche Post AG |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> It gained a foothold in the United States when it acquired [[Airborne Express]].\n\nThe DHL Express financial results are published in the Deutsche Post AG annual report.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2016, this division's revenue increased by 2.7% to \u20ac14 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aircargoweek.com/revenue-falls-earnings-operating-profit-dhl/ |title=Revenue falls, but earnings and operating profit up at DHL |last=Burns |first=Justin |date=8 March 2017 |website=Air Cargo Week |publisher=Azura International |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> The earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT) increased by 11.3% over 2015 to \u20ac1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://postandparcel.info/78601/news/deutsche-post-dhl-reports-record-earnings-for-2016/ |title=Deutsche Post DHL reports \u201crecord earnings\u201d for 2016 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=Post and Parcen |publisher= |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Logo DHL old.svg|thumb|Old DHL logo before its purchase by Deutsche Post AG]]\n[[File:DHL subsidiary on Deutsche Post premises Steinfurt.jpg|thumb|Traditional DHL subsidiary in [[Steinfurt]] (Germany) sharing premises and logistics with Deutsche Post]]\n[[File:Amsterdam-DHL-boat-0524.jpg|thumb|DHL boat in [[Amsterdam]], carrying DHL delivery bicycles on board]]\n[[File:DHL-Tren-de-la-Costa.jpg|thumb|DHL advertising on the [[Tren de la Costa]] light railway, [[Buenos Aires]]]]\n[[File:DHL-AY06EYR.jpg|thumb|DHL semitrailer truck]]\n\n===Origins===\nWhile [[Larry Hillblom]] was studying law at [[University of California, Berkeley]]'s [[UC Berkeley School of Law|Boalt Hall School of Law]] in the late 1960s, he accepted a job as a courier for the insurance company Michael's, Poe & Associates (MPA). He started running courier duty between [[Oakland International Airport]] and [[Los Angeles International Airport]], picking up packages for the last flight of the day, and returning on the first flight the next morning, up to five times a week.<ref name=\"King Larry\">{{cite book |last1=Scurlock |first1=James D. |title=King Larry: The Life and Ruins of an American Billionaire Genius |date=2012 |publisher=Scribner |location=New York |isbn=9781416589228}}</ref>{{rp|12}}\n\nAfter he graduated, Hillblom met with MPA salesman [[Adrian Dalsey]] and they planned to expand MPA's concept of fast delivery to other business enterprises. They flew between [[Honolulu]] and [[Los Angeles]], transporting [[Bill of lading|bills of lading]] for their first client, [[Seatrain Lines]].<ref name=\"King Larry\"/>{{rp|17}}\n\n====The initials====\nHillblom put up a portion of his student loans to start the company, bringing in his two friends [[Adrian Dalsey]] and Robert Lynn as partners, with their combined initials of their surnames as the company name (DHL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-23/news/mn-5041_1_larry-hillblom|title=Larry Hillblom; Co-Founder of DHL Worldwide Express|first=From Times Wire|last=Services|date=23 May 1995|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref> They shared a [[Plymouth Duster]] that they drove around San Francisco to pick up the documents in suitcases, then rushed to the airport to book flights using another relatively new invention, the corporate credit card. As the business took off, they started hiring new couriers to join the company. Their first hires were Max and Blanche Kroll, whose apartment in Hawaii often became a makeshift [[flophouse]] for their couriers.\n\n===Domestic expansion===\nIn the 1970s, DHL became an international delivery company, similar to Loomis and Purolator who were the only other international courier companies at the time. The only major competitor in the overnight market was [[FedEx|Federal Express]] (FedEx), which did not open its first international service until 1981, expanding to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario, Canada]]. Nevertheless, the domestic market was extremely profitable, and DHL was the third largest courier behind FedEx and [[United Parcel Service|UPS]].\n\n===Deutsche Post purchase===\n[[Deutsche Post]] began to acquire [[Share (finance)|shares]] in DHL in 1998, acquiring controlling interest in 2001. By the end of 2002, Deutsche Post had acquired all of DHL's remaining stock, and absorbed the operation into its Express division.<ref name=\"dpdhl.com\"/> The DHL brand was expanded to other Deutsche Post divisions, business units and subsidiaries. Today, DHL Express shares its DHL brand with other Deutsche Post business units, such as [[DHL Global Forwarding]], [[DHL Freight]], [[DHL Supply Chain]], and [[DHL Global Mail]].\n\n* 1999: [[Deutsche Post]] World Net (DPWN) purchased the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] shipping company [[Van Gend & Loos]] as well as Swiss freight forwarder [[Danzas]].{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n* 2001: Deutsche Post acquires a majority (51%) of DHL's shares, and the remaining 49% in 2002. The new DHL is launched by merging the old DHL, Danzas, and Securicor Omega Euro Express.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postandparcel.info/6826/news/deutsche-post-to-buy-the-rest-of-dhl/|title=Deutsche Post to buy the rest of DHL|date=2002-09-01|website=Post & Parcel|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>The [[Packstation]], an automated delivery booth, was introduced as a pilot project in Dortmund and Mainz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipc.be/services/markets-and-regulations/e-commerce-market-insights/e-commerce-articles/parcel-lockers|title=Delivery choice - Parcel lockers|website=International Post Corporation|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n\n=== After 2001 ===\n[[File:G-BIKC DHL-1.JPG|thumb|DHL G-BIKC: ex [[British Airways]] [[Boeing 757]], converted to cargo type in 2001 - Landing at [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid Airport]] (Spain) - Old DHL color scheme and logo]]\n\nIn 2002, DHL Introduced a new red-and-yellow color scheme and logo.\n\nDHL Airways, Inc., which handled all US domestic flights, was renamed [[Astar Air Cargo|ASTAR Air Cargo]] in 2003, following a [[management buyout]]. DHL's airline had over 550 pilots in service in October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/company/CompanyInfo.asp?nav=companyInfo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821192350/http://www.dhl-usa.com/Company/CompanyInfo.asp?nav=companyInfo|title=DHL: Company Information|archivedate=2006-08-21}}</ref> In August 2003, Deutsche Post acquired [[Airborne Express]] and began its integration into DHL. \n\nA planned expansion by DHL at [[Brussels Airport]] created a political crisis in [[Belgium]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurofound.europa.eu/eiro/2004/10/feature/be0410301f.htm |title=DHL expansion controversy leads to strike |publisher=Eurofound.europa.eu |date=2004-10-27 |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> On 21 October 2004, DHL Express announced that it planned to move its European hub from Brussels to [[Leipzig]], Germany ([[Vatry]], [[France]], was also considered but rejected). DHL's [[Trade union|unions]] called a strike in response and paralyzed work for a day. On 8 November 2004, DHL Express invested \u20ac120 million in an [[India]]n domestic courier, [[Blue Dart Aviation|Blue Dart]], becoming the majority shareholder in the company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.com/publish/g0/en/press/release/2004/081104.high.html |title=DHL Global Press Release |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> \n\nIn 2005, Deutsche Post made an offer to buy the contract logistics company [[Exel|Exel plc]], which had just acquired [[Tibbett and Britten|Tibbett & Britten Group]]. On 14 December 2005, Deutsche Post announced the completion of the acquisition of Exel. DHL integrated Exel into its logistics division, rebranding the division's services as [[DHL Supply Chain|DHL Exel Supply Chain]]. Following that acquisition, DHL had a global workforce of 285,000 people (500,000 people including DPWN and other sister companies) and roughly $65 billion in annual sales. \n\nIn 2006, DHL won a ten-year contract worth \u00a31.6 billion to run the [[NHS Supply Chain]], part of the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[National Health Service]]. Under the contract, DHL was responsible for providing logistics services for over 500,000 products to support 600 hospitals and other health providers in the UK.\n\nIn a 50/50 joint venture with [[Lufthansa Cargo]], DHL Express co-founded a new cargo airline, [[AeroLogic]], in 2007, based at [[Leipzig/Halle Airport]]. The carrier operated up to 11 [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777F]] planes by 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2008/01/28/221143/aerologic-outlines-launch-and-expansion-plans.html|title=AeroLogic outlines launch and expansion plans|author=Flight Global|date=2008-01-28|accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> In December 2007, DHL became the first carrier to transport cargo via wind-powered ships, flying [[MS Beluga Skysails]] kites. \n\nAs part of the NHS contract, DHL opened a new {{convert|250000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} distribution centre{{where|date=January 2020}} in 2008 to act as a stock-holding hub for food and other products, with another distribution centre planned for opening in 2012. The two new distribution centres created about 1,000 new jobs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.co.uk/publish/gb/en/press/release/2006/dhl_wins_contract.high.html |title=DHL UK press release |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> In May 2008, DHL Aviation moved its central depot to Leipzig, Germany, leading to improved service and timeliness to the European Union.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In the same month, DHL Express announced restructuring plans for its United States network, including termination of its business relationship with [[ABX Air]] and a new contract with competitor [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] for air freight operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom/PressReleases&year=2008&seq=1207 |title=DHL to restructure U.S. express business |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121183407/http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom%2FPressReleases&year=2008&seq=1207 |archivedate=2008-11-21 }}</ref> Its cargo hub was also shifted from Wilmington to Louisville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/2008/10/20/daily54.html|title=UPS CEO says DHL deal could change|work=Cincinnati Business Courier}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnewsj.com/main.asp?SectionID=49&SubSectionID=156&ArticleID=170480&TM=29295.16|title=Wnewsj.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718075117/http://www.wnewsj.com/main.asp?SectionID=49&SubSectionID=156&ArticleID=170480&TM=29295.16|archivedate=2011-07-18}}</ref> The [[Air Line Pilots Association, International]] protested,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS208313+23-Oct-2008+PRN20081023|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120910185625/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS208313+23-Oct-2008+PRN20081023|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-10|title=ALPA Calls Upon Congress to Hold New Hearings on DHL-UPS Deal|date=2008-10-23|accessdate=2009-08-11|work=Reuters}}</ref> but on 10 November 2008, DHL announced that it was cutting 9,500 jobs as it discontinued domestic air and ground operations within the United States due to economic uncertainty. However, it retained international services and was still in talks with UPS to transport DHL packages between U.S. airports.<ref name=\"money.cnn.com\" /> \n\nDHL ended domestic pickup and delivery service in the United States in 2009, effectively leaving UPS and FedEx as the two major express parcel delivery companies in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom/PressReleases&year=2008&seq=1246|title=DHL: Press Releases|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121135152/http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom%2FPressReleases&year=2008&seq=1246|archivedate=2008-11-21}}</ref> Limited domestic service was still available from DHL, with the packages tendered to [[United States Postal Service|USPS]] for local delivery. In April 2009, UPS announced that DHL and UPS had terminated negotiations without an agreement for UPS to provide airlift for DHL packages between airports in North America. DHL said in a statement, \"We have not been able to come to a conclusive agreement that is acceptable to both parties.\" DHL continued to use its current air cargo providers, ASTAR Air Cargo and ABX Air.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/30267640 |title=UPS, DHL Scrap Airlift Agreement Talks |author=CNBC |accessdate=2009-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the company opened a newly expanded and upgraded global hub at the [[Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport]] in [[Erlanger, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northernkentuckyusa.com/newsroom/2013/06/13/gov-beshear-participates-in-ribbon-cutting-for-dhls-global-hub-in-northern-kentucky.aspx |title=Gov. Beshear Participates in Ribbon-Cutting for DHL's Global Hub in Northern Kentucky |access-date=11 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714190007/http://www.northernkentuckyusa.com/newsroom/2013/06/13/gov-beshear-participates-in-ribbon-cutting-for-dhls-global-hub-in-northern-kentucky.aspx |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n[[File:DHL - Deutsche Post in Tokio.jpg|thumb|DHL van in Tokyo]]\nDHL Express's global headquarters are part of the Deutsche Post headquarters in Bonn.\n\nHeadquarters for the [[Americas]] are located in [[Plantation, Florida]], USA, while its Asia-Pacific and emerging markets headquarters are located in [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Hong Kong]], and [[China]]. The European hub is in [[Leipzig]], Germany.\n\nMost of DHL Express' business is incorporated as DHL International GmbH.\n\nMajor competitors include [[FedEx]], [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] and national post carriers such as [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) and [[Royal Mail]]. However, DHL has a minor partnership with the USPS, which allows DHL to deliver small packages to the recipient through the USPS network known as DHL Global Mail, now known as DHL eCommerce. It is also the sole provider for transferring USPS mail in and out of [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].\n\nDHL offers worldwide services, including deliveries to countries such as Iraq, Afghanistan and [[Myanmar]] (formerly Burma). As it is German-owned, DHL is not affected by U.S. [[embargo]]es or sanctions and will ship to [[Cuba]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dhl.com/en/cu/country_profile.html |title=Cuba |author=DHL |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> and [[North Korea]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.com/en/kp/country_profile.html |title=Korea |author=DHL |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref><ref name=\"PYT DHL in DPRK\">{{cite news|last=Jong|first=Hwa Sun|title=DHL office works well in Pyongyang|newspaper=Pyongyang times|date=May 12, 2012|location=George Washington University}}</ref> However, there are strict codes for delivering to North Korea, as the country has shaky relations with the West.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAs DHL is no longer a United States company, it is not allowed to make domestic flights between U.S. airports. DHL contracts these services to other providers.<ref name=\"money.cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/11/10/news/companies/dhl/index.htm |title=DHL cuts 9,500 U.S. jobs |author=Aaron Smith |accessdate=2008-11-10 | work=CNN | date=2008-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental record==\nDHL has taken measures to control their environmental effect by use of alternative fuel vehicles. DHL changed vehicles in certain delivery fleets in order to use alternative fuels. Certain new vehicles use [[compressed natural gas]], to which DHL hopes to convert 50% of their vehicles in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ngvglobal.com/sp/market-developments/dhl-makes-cng-alternative-fuel-of-choice-in-uae.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120529155030/http://www.ngvglobal.com/sp/market-developments/dhl-makes-cng-alternative-fuel-of-choice-in-uae.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 May 2012 |date=24 March 2007 |accessdate=9 December 2012 |title=DHL Makes CNG Alternative Fuel of Choice in UAE |work=NGVGglobal.com }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2005, DHL won a High Court injunction establishing an exclusion zone around each of its 288 buildings in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] as well as the homes of its 18,000 UK employees. The firm has been the subject of a campaign of intimidation because of their business with [[Huntingdon Life Sciences]]. The judge banned protesters from coming within {{convert|50|yd|m}} of any DHL premises or the homes of their employees as well as any organized demonstration within {{convert|100|yd|m}} unless the police had been given four hours' notice. The injunction also protects anyone doing business with DHL from intimidation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vare.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13&Itemid=2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227085837/http://www.vare.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13&Itemid=2|archivedate=2008-12-27|url-status=dead|title=DHL obtains court injunction |work=Victims of Animal Rights Extremism |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Use of electric vehicles ===\n[[File:2016-12-10-Post Streetscooter-9409.jpg|thumb|Electric StreetScooter Work (2016)]]\n\nIn December 2014 Deutsche Post DHL purchased the [[StreetScooter]] company, a small manufacturer of electric vehicles as part of its long-term goal to reach zero emissions in its delivery operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/de/presse/pressemitteilungen/2014/deutsche_post_dhl_uebernimmt_streetscooter_gmbh.html |title=Deutsche Post DHL \u00fcbernimmt StreetScooter GmbH |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=9 December 2014 |website=Deutsche Post DHL |publisher=Deutsche Post AG |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Deutsche Post DHL hat den Kaufvertrag f\u00fcr die StreetScooter GmbH unterzeichnet - ein ehemaliges Start-up aus dem Umfeld der RWTH Aachen mit dem Ziel, wirtschaftliche Elektroautos zu entwickeln. Mit der \u00dcbernahme der StreetScooter GmbH, die noch unter dem Vorbehalt der fusionskontrollrechtlichen Freigabe steht, \u00fcbernimmt Deutsche Post DHL auch die Entwicklungs- und Produktionsrechte an den Fahrzeugen sowie die Mitarbeiter. Die StreetScooter GmbH ist ein Spin-Off der RWTH Aachen und als Konsortium aus rund 80 Industrieunternehmen der Automobilindustrie und verwandter Branchen gestartet. Es wurde 2010 gegr\u00fcndet und besch\u00e4ftigt 70 Mitarbeiter. Seit 2013 sind in Aachen im ehemaligen Talbot-/Bombardierwerk rund 200 StreetScooter Fahrzeuge produziert worden.}}</ref> By year end 2016, some 2,000 vehicles had been produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/unternehmen/der-tausendste-elektro-streetscooter-der-deutschen-post-14401894.html |title=Streetscooter - Der tausendste Elektro-Transporter der Post |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 August 2016 |website=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung  |publisher=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung GmbH |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Die Post will ihren gesamten Fuhrpark auf Elektro-Autos umstellen. Bis dahin dauert es noch. Einen wichtigen Schritt hat das Unternehmen nun aber gemacht.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-24/even-germany-s-post-office-is-building-an-electric-car |title=Even Germany's Post Office Is Building an Electric Car |last=Weiss |first=Richard |date=24 March 2017 |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=When Deutsche Post AG couldn't find a zero-emission delivery van that met its needs, it bought a startup and developed one.}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, electric vans with a much greater range will be required to achieve the long-term goal of replacing the entire Deutsche Post and DHL Express fleet of approximately 70,000 vehicles with StreetScooter models.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/deutsche-post-dhl-makes-its-own-electric-delivery-vans/a-19332124 |title=Deutsche Post DHL makes its own electric delivery vans |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 June 2016 |website=DW |publisher=Deutsche Welle |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Provided its StreetScooters can be produced cheaply enough compared to the alternative of buying e-vans from established auto makers, the bottom line of the world's biggest delivery services company stands to benefit from producing its own delivery vehicles - whether or not it eventually adds profits from sales of e-vans to third parties.}}</ref>\n\nThe Deutsche Post/DHL GoGreen program plans to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases and local air pollutants; the company has four interim goals for doing so, to be achieved by the year 2025. The long-term goal, summarized by Frank Appel, Chief Executive Officer, is more aggressive. \"From now until 2050, our mission will be to drive our business toward zero [logistics related] emissions. We are setting the standard for the future of the transport sector and doing our part to help the world community reach its goal of limiting global warming to less than two degrees Celsius.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/responsibility/environmental-protection/gogreen_program.html |title=2017 Deutsche Post AG Our GoGreen environmental protection program |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=DP DHL |publisher=Deutsche Post |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=By the year 2050 we want to reduce all logistics-related emissions to zero \u2013 a highly ambitious goal. To ensure progress towards the 2050 zero-emissions target, we have set four interim goals to be achieved by the year 2025.}}</ref>\n\n[[BYD Auto|BYD]] supplies DHL with electric distribution fleet of commercial [[BYD T3]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bydeurope.com/news/news.php?action=readnews&page=3&nid=216|title=BYD supplies DHL with electric distribution fleet|author=bydeurope.com|publisher=bydeurope.com|date=2016-01-15|accessdate=2016-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719233328/http://www.bydeurope.com/news/news.php?action=readnews&page=3&nid=216|archive-date=19 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==DHL aviation==\n{{Main|DHL Aviation}}\n[[File:HP-1810DAE (7010604717) (3).jpg|thumb|DHL Aero Expreso Boeing 757-200F]]\nDeutsche Post owns five airline subsidiaries operating for DHL Express, operating approx. 250 aircraft and another 21 aircraft on orders, which are collectively referred to as [[DHL Aviation]]. DHL Express is an equal partner in a sixth airline that operates for DHL Express:\n* '''[[Blue Dart Aviation]]''', [[Chennai]], [[India]], provides services for Indian destinations from [[Chennai International Airport]]\n* '''[[DHL Aero Expreso]]''', [[Panama City]], [[Panama]] provides services for destinations in Central and South America\n* '''[[DHL Air UK]]''', [[Hounslow]], [[United Kingdom]] provides services for European destinations from [[East Midlands Airport]]\n* '''[[European Air Transport Leipzig]]''', [[Leipzig]], [[Germany]] provides services for European destinations from [[Leipzig/Halle Airport]]\n* '''[[AeroLogic]]''' (''joint venture with [[Lufthansa]]''), [[Schkeuditz]], [[Germany]] provides services from Europe to central and eastern Asian destinations from Leipzig/Halle Airport and [[Frankfurt Airport]]\n* '''[[DHL International Aviation ME|SNAS/DHL]]''', [[Bahrain]] provides services for [[Middle East]] destinations from [[Bahrain International Airport]]\n\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Pair of RS Spyders.jpg|thumb|DHL-colored [[Team Penske]] [[Porsche RS Spyder]] LMP2 racing cars of [[Penske Racing]]]]\nFor several years, DHL was the primary sponsor of the [[Porsche RS Spyder]] [[Le Mans Prototype]]s in the [[International Motor Sports Association]] [[American Le Mans Series]]. DHL also sponsors [[Ryan Hunter-Reay]]'s #28 [[IndyCar Series]] car for [[Andretti Autosport]] since 2011. With DHL, Hunter-Reay won the championship for the [[2012 IndyCar Series season]] as well as the [[2014 Indianapolis 500]]. DHL were the main title sponsor of the [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] [[Formula One]] team during [[2002 Formula One season|2002]]. Since then, DHL has become a regular track-side sponsor at various races throughout each year, as well as becoming the 'Official Logistics Partner' of the sport. Since 2007, they also sponsor the [[DHL Fastest Lap Award]] for the driver that achieves the most fastest laps in a season.<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/642713/dhl-sponsor-formula-1s-fastest-laps-trophy/| title = DHL to sponsor Formula 1's fastest laps trophy| publisher = Brand Republic| accessdate = 16 November 2015}}</ref> \n[[File:Jordan GP 2002 sato.jpg|thumb|A [[Jordan Grand Prix]] Formula One car with a DHL paint scheme at the US Grand Prix at the Indianapolis track.]]\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United Football Club]] announced them as their first training kit sponsor in August 2011, agreeing to a four-year deal with DHL reported to be worth \u00a340&nbsp;million; it is believed to be the first instance of training kit sponsorship in English football.<ref>{{cite news |title=DHL delivers new shirt deal |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Club-News/2011/Aug/DHL-delivers-ground-breaking-deal.aspx |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United unveils two new commercial deals |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-14615711 |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref> In 2014, [[FC Bayern Munich]] agreed to a six-year sponsorship deal with DHL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.de/en/news/news/2014/fcb-and-dhl-announce-partnership-220814.php|title=FCB and DHL announce partnership - FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen AG|work=FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen AG}}</ref> In 2012, the company became the main sponsor of [[League of Ireland]] club [[Bohemian F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.extratime.ie/newsdesk/articles/7567/|title=Bohs agree sponsorship deal with DHL - Extratime.ie - League of Ireland|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313020048/http://extratime.ie/newsdesk/articles/7567/|archivedate=2012-03-13}}</ref>\n\nDHL is the current title sponsor of the South African Western Cape Rugby Union teams [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] and the [[Stormers]]. This is came into effect on 1 January 2011 for a period of three years.<ref name=\"stormers_sponsorship\">{{cite web|url=http://thestormers.com/dhl-new-sponsor-for-wp-stormers-rugby/ |title=DHL new sponsor for WP/ Stormers Rugby |publisher=The Stormers |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> DHL are still the current sponsor for both teams as of the 2017/18 season.\n\nFor the [[2011\u201312 Volvo Ocean Race]] DHL was one of four race partners providing logistics for this event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volvooceanrace.com/en/partners/4_DHL.html|title=Volvo Ocean Race|author=Volvo Ocean Race|work=Volvo Ocean Race|access-date=21 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125182003/http://www.volvooceanrace.com/en/partners/4_DHL.html|archive-date=25 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>And AFC Champions league Official Timing and Logistics Partner</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the company is sponsoring, with IMG Fashion, ''DHL Exported'', which is aimed at \"assisting designers who are already successful locally to gain momentum internationally\".<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/a-global-boost-7409299?src=nl/mornReport/20140205 | title=DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers | publisher=WWD | date=5 February 2014 | accessdate=5 February 2014 | author=Lockwood, Lisa}}</ref> DHL Exported will \"sponsor a chosen designer for two consecutive seasons at\" the Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week in New York, London Fashion Week, Milan Fashion Week or Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week Tokyo.<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\"/> IMG Fashion \"will accept applications from February 17 through April 2 at {{URL|dhlexported.com}}\".<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\"/>\n\nExpanding its support to various cultural endeavors, DHL signed as the Official Logistics partner for Cirque du Soleil. DHL transports up to 2,000 tonnes and 80 freight containers utilizing air, sea, and land to transport the equipment from one city to the next.<ref>[https://www.dhl.com/en/about_us/partnerships/music_and_arts/cirque_du_soleil.html DHL. \"Partnerships: Cirque du Soleil.\" Retrieved June 20, 2016]</ref>\n \nIn 2015 DHL became the main sponsor of Italian volleyball club [[Modena Volley]], covering the whole men's [[Italian Volleyball League|SuperLega Italian championship]] and the [[CEV Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/fridays_daily_deal_round_up_love_raina_and_mor | title=Friday's Daily Deal round-up: Love, Raina and more| publisher=SportsProMedia | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=8 October 2015 | author=Kennedy, Mike}}</ref>\n\nDHL is a major sponsor of [[Surf Life Saving Australia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sls.com.au/partners/|title=Partners - Surf Life Saving|newspaper=Surf Life Saving|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n\n* In 2002, [[2002 \u00dcberlingen mid-air collision|Bashkirian Airlines Flight 2937]], a [[Tupolev Tu-154]] passenger jet, collided with DHL Flight 611, a [[Boeing 757#757-200|Boeing 757-200]] cargo jet at {{convert|35000|ft|m|abbr=on}} over [[\u00dcberlingen]], Germany. All 69 passengers on board the Bashkiran flight (consisting mainly of Russian schoolchildren) and the two pilots of DHL were killed.<ref name=\"PCI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/2002/2002-38.htm|title=Information regarding the air accident|author=PlaneCrashInfo.com|accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref name=\"AD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=07012002&reg=RA-85816&airline=Bashkirian+Airlines|title=Information regarding the air accident|author=AirDisaster.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228171058/http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=07012002&reg=RA-85816&airline=Bashkirian+Airlines|archivedate=2014-02-28|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\n* In 22 November 2003, [[2003 Baghdad DHL attempted shootdown incident|DHL shootdown incident in Baghdad]] wherein Iraqi insurgents fired an [[9K32 Strela-2|SA-7 \"Grail\"]] [[surface-to-air missile]] at a [[European Air Transport]] [[Airbus A300]] operating on behalf of DHL. The aircraft took off from [[Baghdad]] airport whereupon the missile struck the left wing, disabling all three [[Hydraulic drive system|hydraulic systems]] and set the wing on fire. The aircraft began a dangerous [[phugoid]] (vertical oscillation) but the crew managed to land safely at the airport, despite only being able to control the aircraft by adjusting the engine thrust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightsafety.org/citations/dhl_cit.html|title=DHL|author=Flight Safety|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505001324/http://www.flightsafety.org/citations/dhl_cit.html|archivedate=May 5, 2008|accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref>\n*In October 2008, two DHL Express Middle East senior executives, David Giles and Jason Bresler, were assassinated in Kabul, by one of their own Afghan employees; they received military honors by the U.S. military, the first of such kind in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Story.asp?Article=233511&Sn=BNEW&IssueID=31228%7ctitle=Gulf-daily-news.com%7cpublisher=|title=Gulf Daily News \u00bb Local News \u00bb DHL official is mourned|work=gulf-daily-news.com}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2010, A DHL [[Antonov An-26]] aircraft made an emergency landing on the frozen [[Lake \u00dclemiste]], close to [[Tallinn Airport|Lennart Meri Tallinn Airport]]. Initial reports indicated problems with the landing gear and one of the engines. The flight was operated by [[Exin]] on behalf of DHL. The aircraft involved was SP-FDO and the flight departed from Helsinki Airport. Two of the six crew members were injured.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[DHL Balloon]]\n* [[Major League Baseball Reliever of the Year Award#Delivery Man Award (2005\u20132013)|Delivery Man Award (2005\u20132013)]]\n* [[DHL Fastest Lap Award]]\n*[[Wilmington, Ohio]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dhl.com}}\n* [http://www.globalaviationresource.com/reports/2009/dhlhubeastmidlands.php Major DHL Express feature on Global Aviation Resource]\n\n{{Deutsche Post}}\n{{British Royal Warrant holders}}\n{{Trucking industry in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:DHL Express ]]\n[[Category:Express mail]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Broward County, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DHL\n| trading_name = \n| logo = [[File:DHL Logo.svg|280px]]\n| type = [[division (business)|Division]]\n| parent = [[Deutsche Post]]\n| foundation = [[San Francisco]], [[California|CA]]<br /> ({{start date and age|1969}})\n| location = [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]\n| key_people = Ken Allen <small>([[Chairman]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/investors/corporate_governance/board_of_management/members/ken_allen.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL - Ken Allen|publisher=}}</ref>\n| founders = <br>Adrian Dalsey <br>Larry Hillblom <br>Robert Lynn\n| industry = [[Courier|Express logistics]]\n| num_employees = {{increase}} 380,000 (2019)\n| products = DHL Express Worldwide <br> DHL Express 9:00 <br> DHL Express 12:00\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.dhl.com/en.html}}\n}}\n'''DHL (Dalsey, Hillblom and Lynn) International GmbH''' is an American and German courier, parcel, and [[express mail]] service which is a [[division (business)|division]] of the German [[logistics]] company [[Deutsche Post|Deutsche Post DHL]]. Deutsche Post DHL is the world's largest logistics company,<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=https://www.dhl.com/publish/content/g0/en/about/divisions.low.html |title=DHL Divisions |author=DHL/DPAG |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref>  now in over 220 countries and territories worldwide,{{cn|date=September 2019}} particularly in sea and air mail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manager-magazin.de/magazin/artikel/0,2828,708038-4,00.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL: Kunde statt Chaos - manager magazin - Unternehmen|date=22 July 2010|work=manager magazin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gate4logistics.de/logistik-karriere/top-10-unternehmen.html|title=Top 10 Unternehmen|date=12 June 2013|access-date=1 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110081514/http://www.gate4logistics.de/logistik-karriere/top-10-unternehmen.html|archive-date=10 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company delivers over 1.3 billion parcels per year.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.logistics.dhl/global-en/home/about-us.html |title=Company Portrait |website=DHL Company Portrait |access-date=1 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe company was founded in the United States in 1969 and expanded its service throughout the world by the late 1970s. The company was primarily interested in offshore and intercontinental deliveries, but the success of [[FedEx]] prompted their own intra-US expansion starting in 1983.\n\nIn 1998, Deutsche Post began to acquire shares in DHL. It reached controlling interest in 2001, and acquired all outstanding shares by December 2002.<ref name=\"dpdhl.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/about_us/history.html|title=Deutsche Post DHL Group - History|website=www.dpdhl.com}}</ref> The company then absorbed DHL into its Express division, while expanding the use of the DHL brand to other Deutsche Post divisions, business units, and subsidiaries. Today, DHL Express shares its DHL brand with business units such as [[DHL Global Forwarding]] and [[DHL Supply Chain]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/content/dam/dpdhl/Investors/Events/Reporting/2017/FY2016/DPDHL_2016_Annual_Report.pdf |title=2016 Report |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=DPHL |publisher=Deutsche Post AG |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> It gained a foothold in the United States when it acquired [[Airborne Express]].\n\nThe DHL Express financial results are published in the Deutsche Post AG annual report.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2016, this division's revenue increased by 2.7% to \u20ac14 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aircargoweek.com/revenue-falls-earnings-operating-profit-dhl/ |title=Revenue falls, but earnings and operating profit up at DHL |last=Burns |first=Justin |date=8 March 2017 |website=Air Cargo Week |publisher=Azura International |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> The earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT) increased by 11.3% over 2015 to \u20ac1.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://postandparcel.info/78601/news/deutsche-post-dhl-reports-record-earnings-for-2016/ |title=Deutsche Post DHL reports \u201crecord earnings\u201d for 2016 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=Post and Parcen |publisher= |access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Logo DHL old.svg|thumb|Old DHL logo before its purchase by Deutsche Post AG]]\n[[File:DHL subsidiary on Deutsche Post premises Steinfurt.jpg|thumb|Traditional DHL subsidiary in [[Steinfurt]] (Germany) sharing premises and logistics with Deutsche Post]]\n[[File:Amsterdam-DHL-boat-0524.jpg|thumb|DHL boat in [[Amsterdam]], carrying DHL delivery bicycles on board]]\n[[File:DHL-Tren-de-la-Costa.jpg|thumb|DHL advertising on the [[Tren de la Costa]] light railway, [[Buenos Aires]]]]\n[[File:DHL-AY06EYR.jpg|thumb|DHL semitrailer truck]]\n\n===Origins===\nWhile [[Larry Hillblom]] was studying law at [[University of California, Berkeley]]'s [[UC Berkeley School of Law|Boalt Hall School of Law]] in the late 1960s, he accepted a job as a courier for the insurance company Michael's, Poe & Associates (MPA). He started running courier duty between [[Oakland International Airport]] and [[Los Angeles International Airport]], picking up packages for the last flight of the day, and returning on the first flight the next morning, up to five times a week.<ref name=\"King Larry\">{{cite book |last1=Scurlock |first1=James D. |title=King Larry: The Life and Ruins of an American Billionaire Genius |date=2012 |publisher=Scribner |location=New York |isbn=9781416589228}}</ref>{{rp|12}}\n\nAfter he graduated, Hillblom met with MPA salesman [[Adrian Dalsey]] and they planned to expand MPA's concept of fast delivery to other business enterprises. They flew between [[Honolulu]] and [[Los Angeles]], transporting [[Bill of lading|bills of lading]] for their first client, [[Seatrain Lines]].<ref name=\"King Larry\"/>{{rp|17}}\n\n====The initials====\nHillblom put up a portion of his student loans to start the company, bringing in his two friends [[Adrian Dalsey]] and Robert Lynn as partners, with their combined initials of their surnames as the company name (DHL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-23/news/mn-5041_1_larry-hillblom|title=Larry Hillblom; Co-Founder of DHL Worldwide Express|first=From Times Wire|last=Services|date=23 May 1995|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref> They shared a [[Plymouth Duster]] that they drove around San Francisco to pick up the documents in suitcases, then rushed to the airport to book flights using another relatively new invention, the corporate credit card. As the business took off, they started hiring new couriers to join the company. Their first hires were Max and Blanche Kroll, whose apartment in Hawaii often became a makeshift [[flophouse]] for their couriers.\n\n===Domestic expansion===\nIn the 1970s, DHL became an international delivery company, similar to Loomis and Purolator who were the only other international courier companies at the time. The only major competitor in the overnight market was [[FedEx|Federal Express]] (FedEx), which did not open its first international service until 1981, expanding to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario, Canada]]. Nevertheless, the domestic market was extremely profitable, and DHL was the third largest courier behind FedEx and [[United Parcel Service|UPS]].\n\n===Deutsche Post purchase===\n[[Deutsche Post]] began to acquire [[Share (finance)|shares]] in DHL in 1998, acquiring controlling interest in 2001. By the end of 2002, Deutsche Post had acquired all of DHL's remaining stock, and absorbed the operation into its Express division.<ref name=\"dpdhl.com\"/> The DHL brand was expanded to other Deutsche Post divisions, business units and subsidiaries. Today, DHL Express shares its DHL brand with other Deutsche Post business units, such as [[DHL Global Forwarding]], [[DHL Freight]], [[DHL Supply Chain]], and [[DHL Global Mail]].\n\n* 1999: [[Deutsche Post]] World Net (DPWN) purchased the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] shipping company [[Van Gend & Loos]] as well as Swiss freight forwarder [[Danzas]].{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n* 2001: Deutsche Post acquires a majority (51%) of DHL's shares, and the remaining 49% in 2002. The new DHL is launched by merging the old DHL, Danzas, and Securicor Omega Euro Express.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postandparcel.info/6826/news/deutsche-post-to-buy-the-rest-of-dhl/|title=Deutsche Post to buy the rest of DHL|date=2002-09-01|website=Post & Parcel|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>The [[Packstation]], an automated delivery booth, was introduced as a pilot project in Dortmund and Mainz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipc.be/services/markets-and-regulations/e-commerce-market-insights/e-commerce-articles/parcel-lockers|title=Delivery choice - Parcel lockers|website=International Post Corporation|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n\n=== After 2001 ===\n[[File:G-BIKC DHL-1.JPG|thumb|DHL G-BIKC: ex [[British Airways]] [[Boeing 757]], converted to cargo type in 2001 - Landing at [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez Madrid\u2013Barajas Airport|Madrid Airport]] (Spain) - Old DHL color scheme and logo]]\n\nIn 2002, DHL Introduced a new red-and-yellow color scheme and logo.\n\nDHL Airways, Inc., which handled all US domestic flights, was renamed [[Astar Air Cargo|ASTAR Air Cargo]] in 2003, following a [[management buyout]]. DHL's airline had over 550 pilots in service in October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/company/CompanyInfo.asp?nav=companyInfo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821192350/http://www.dhl-usa.com/Company/CompanyInfo.asp?nav=companyInfo|title=DHL: Company Information|archivedate=2006-08-21}}</ref> In August 2003, Deutsche Post acquired [[Airborne Express]] and began its integration into DHL. \n\nA planned expansion by DHL at [[Brussels Airport]] created a political crisis in [[Belgium]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurofound.europa.eu/eiro/2004/10/feature/be0410301f.htm |title=DHL expansion controversy leads to strike |publisher=Eurofound.europa.eu |date=2004-10-27 |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> On 21 October 2004, DHL Express announced that it planned to move its European hub from Brussels to [[Leipzig]], Germany ([[Vatry]], [[France]], was also considered but rejected). DHL's [[Trade union|unions]] called a strike in response and paralyzed work for a day. On 8 November 2004, DHL Express invested \u20ac120 million in an [[India]]n domestic courier, [[Blue Dart Aviation|Blue Dart]], becoming the majority shareholder in the company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.com/publish/g0/en/press/release/2004/081104.high.html |title=DHL Global Press Release |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> \n\nIn 2005, Deutsche Post made an offer to buy the contract logistics company [[Exel|Exel plc]], which had just acquired [[Tibbett and Britten|Tibbett & Britten Group]]. On 14 December 2005, Deutsche Post announced the completion of the acquisition of Exel. DHL integrated Exel into its logistics division, rebranding the division's services as [[DHL Supply Chain|DHL Exel Supply Chain]]. Following that acquisition, DHL had a global workforce of 285,000 people (500,000 people including DPWN and other sister companies) and roughly $65 billion in annual sales. \n\nIn 2006, DHL won a ten-year contract worth \u00a31.6 billion to run the [[NHS Supply Chain]], part of the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[National Health Service]]. Under the contract, DHL was responsible for providing logistics services for over 500,000 products to support 600 hospitals and other health providers in the UK.\n\nIn a 50/50 joint venture with [[Lufthansa Cargo]], DHL Express co-founded a new cargo airline, [[AeroLogic]], in 2007, based at [[Leipzig/Halle Airport]]. The carrier operated up to 11 [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777F]] planes by 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2008/01/28/221143/aerologic-outlines-launch-and-expansion-plans.html|title=AeroLogic outlines launch and expansion plans|author=Flight Global|date=2008-01-28|accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> In December 2007, DHL became the first carrier to transport cargo via wind-powered ships, flying [[MS Beluga Skysails]] kites. \n\nAs part of the NHS contract, DHL opened a new {{convert|250000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} distribution centre{{where|date=January 2020}} in 2008 to act as a stock-holding hub for food and other products, with another distribution centre planned for opening in 2012. The two new distribution centres created about 1,000 new jobs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.co.uk/publish/gb/en/press/release/2006/dhl_wins_contract.high.html |title=DHL UK press release |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref> In May 2008, DHL Aviation moved its central depot to Leipzig, Germany, leading to improved service and timeliness to the European Union.{{cn|date=January 2020}} In the same month, DHL Express announced restructuring plans for its United States network, including termination of its business relationship with [[ABX Air]] and a new contract with competitor [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] for air freight operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom/PressReleases&year=2008&seq=1207 |title=DHL to restructure U.S. express business |author=DHL |accessdate=2008-10-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121183407/http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom%2FPressReleases&year=2008&seq=1207 |archivedate=2008-11-21 }}</ref> Its cargo hub was also shifted from Wilmington to Louisville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/2008/10/20/daily54.html|title=UPS CEO says DHL deal could change|work=Cincinnati Business Courier}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnewsj.com/main.asp?SectionID=49&SubSectionID=156&ArticleID=170480&TM=29295.16|title=Wnewsj.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718075117/http://www.wnewsj.com/main.asp?SectionID=49&SubSectionID=156&ArticleID=170480&TM=29295.16|archivedate=2011-07-18}}</ref> The [[Air Line Pilots Association, International]] protested,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS208313+23-Oct-2008+PRN20081023|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120910185625/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS208313+23-Oct-2008+PRN20081023|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-10|title=ALPA Calls Upon Congress to Hold New Hearings on DHL-UPS Deal|date=2008-10-23|accessdate=2009-08-11|work=Reuters}}</ref> but on 10 November 2008, DHL announced that it was cutting 9,500 jobs as it discontinued domestic air and ground operations within the United States due to economic uncertainty. However, it retained international services and was still in talks with UPS to transport DHL packages between U.S. airports.<ref name=\"money.cnn.com\" /> \n\nDHL ended domestic pickup and delivery service in the United States in 2009, effectively leaving UPS and FedEx as the two major express parcel delivery companies in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom/PressReleases&year=2008&seq=1246|title=DHL: Press Releases|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121135152/http://www.dhl-usa.com/about/pr/PRDetail.asp?nav=PressRoom%2FPressReleases&year=2008&seq=1246|archivedate=2008-11-21}}</ref> Limited domestic service was still available from DHL, with the packages tendered to [[United States Postal Service|USPS]] for local delivery. In April 2009, UPS announced that DHL and UPS had terminated negotiations without an agreement for UPS to provide airlift for DHL packages between airports in North America. DHL said in a statement, \"We have not been able to come to a conclusive agreement that is acceptable to both parties.\" DHL continued to use its current air cargo providers, ASTAR Air Cargo and ABX Air.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/30267640 |title=UPS, DHL Scrap Airlift Agreement Talks |author=CNBC |accessdate=2009-09-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the company opened a newly expanded and upgraded global hub at the [[Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport]] in [[Erlanger, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northernkentuckyusa.com/newsroom/2013/06/13/gov-beshear-participates-in-ribbon-cutting-for-dhls-global-hub-in-northern-kentucky.aspx |title=Gov. Beshear Participates in Ribbon-Cutting for DHL's Global Hub in Northern Kentucky |access-date=11 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714190007/http://www.northernkentuckyusa.com/newsroom/2013/06/13/gov-beshear-participates-in-ribbon-cutting-for-dhls-global-hub-in-northern-kentucky.aspx |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n[[File:DHL - Deutsche Post in Tokio.jpg|thumb|DHL van in Tokyo]]\nDHL Express's global headquarters are part of the Deutsche Post headquarters in Bonn.\n\nHeadquarters for the [[Americas]] are located in [[Plantation, Florida]], USA, while its Asia-Pacific and emerging markets headquarters are located in [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Hong Kong]], and [[China]]. The European hub is in [[Leipzig]], Germany.\n\nMost of DHL Express' business is incorporated as DHL International GmbH.\n\nMajor competitors include [[FedEx]], [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] and national post carriers such as [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) and [[Royal Mail]]. However, DHL has a minor partnership with the USPS, which allows DHL to deliver small packages to the recipient through the USPS network known as DHL Global Mail, now known as DHL eCommerce. It is also the sole provider for transferring USPS mail in and out of [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].\n\nDHL offers worldwide services, including deliveries to countries such as Iraq, Afghanistan and [[Myanmar]] (formerly Burma). As it is German-owned, DHL is not affected by U.S. [[embargo]]es or sanctions and will ship to [[Cuba]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dhl.com/en/cu/country_profile.html |title=Cuba |author=DHL |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> and [[North Korea]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhl.com/en/kp/country_profile.html |title=Korea |author=DHL |accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref><ref name=\"PYT DHL in DPRK\">{{cite news|last=Jong|first=Hwa Sun|title=DHL office works well in Pyongyang|newspaper=Pyongyang times|date=May 12, 2012|location=George Washington University}}</ref> However, there are strict codes for delivering to North Korea, as the country has shaky relations with the West.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAs DHL is no longer a United States company, it is not allowed to make domestic flights between U.S. airports. DHL contracts these services to other providers.<ref name=\"money.cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/11/10/news/companies/dhl/index.htm |title=DHL cuts 9,500 U.S. jobs |author=Aaron Smith |accessdate=2008-11-10 | work=CNN | date=2008-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental record==\nDHL has taken measures to control their environmental effect by use of alternative fuel vehicles. DHL changed vehicles in certain delivery fleets in order to use alternative fuels. Certain new vehicles use [[compressed natural gas]], to which DHL hopes to convert 50% of their vehicles in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ngvglobal.com/sp/market-developments/dhl-makes-cng-alternative-fuel-of-choice-in-uae.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120529155030/http://www.ngvglobal.com/sp/market-developments/dhl-makes-cng-alternative-fuel-of-choice-in-uae.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 May 2012 |date=24 March 2007 |accessdate=9 December 2012 |title=DHL Makes CNG Alternative Fuel of Choice in UAE |work=NGVGglobal.com }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2005, DHL won a High Court injunction establishing an exclusion zone around each of its 288 buildings in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] as well as the homes of its 18,000 UK employees. The firm has been the subject of a campaign of intimidation because of their business with [[Huntingdon Life Sciences]]. The judge banned protesters from coming within {{convert|50|yd|m}} of any DHL premises or the homes of their employees as well as any organized demonstration within {{convert|100|yd|m}} unless the police had been given four hours' notice. The injunction also protects anyone doing business with DHL from intimidation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vare.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13&Itemid=2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227085837/http://www.vare.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13&Itemid=2|archivedate=2008-12-27|url-status=dead|title=DHL obtains court injunction |work=Victims of Animal Rights Extremism |accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Use of electric vehicles ===\n[[File:2016-12-10-Post Streetscooter-9409.jpg|thumb|Electric StreetScooter Work (2016)]]\n\nIn December 2014 Deutsche Post DHL purchased the [[StreetScooter]] company, a small manufacturer of electric vehicles as part of its long-term goal to reach zero emissions in its delivery operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/de/presse/pressemitteilungen/2014/deutsche_post_dhl_uebernimmt_streetscooter_gmbh.html |title=Deutsche Post DHL \u00fcbernimmt StreetScooter GmbH |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=9 December 2014 |website=Deutsche Post DHL |publisher=Deutsche Post AG |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Deutsche Post DHL hat den Kaufvertrag f\u00fcr die StreetScooter GmbH unterzeichnet - ein ehemaliges Start-up aus dem Umfeld der RWTH Aachen mit dem Ziel, wirtschaftliche Elektroautos zu entwickeln. Mit der \u00dcbernahme der StreetScooter GmbH, die noch unter dem Vorbehalt der fusionskontrollrechtlichen Freigabe steht, \u00fcbernimmt Deutsche Post DHL auch die Entwicklungs- und Produktionsrechte an den Fahrzeugen sowie die Mitarbeiter. Die StreetScooter GmbH ist ein Spin-Off der RWTH Aachen und als Konsortium aus rund 80 Industrieunternehmen der Automobilindustrie und verwandter Branchen gestartet. Es wurde 2010 gegr\u00fcndet und besch\u00e4ftigt 70 Mitarbeiter. Seit 2013 sind in Aachen im ehemaligen Talbot-/Bombardierwerk rund 200 StreetScooter Fahrzeuge produziert worden.}}</ref> By year end 2016, some 2,000 vehicles had been produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/unternehmen/der-tausendste-elektro-streetscooter-der-deutschen-post-14401894.html |title=Streetscooter - Der tausendste Elektro-Transporter der Post |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=23 August 2016 |website=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung  |publisher=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung GmbH |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Die Post will ihren gesamten Fuhrpark auf Elektro-Autos umstellen. Bis dahin dauert es noch. Einen wichtigen Schritt hat das Unternehmen nun aber gemacht.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-03-24/even-germany-s-post-office-is-building-an-electric-car |title=Even Germany's Post Office Is Building an Electric Car |last=Weiss |first=Richard |date=24 March 2017 |website=Bloomberg |publisher=Bloomberg |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=When Deutsche Post AG couldn't find a zero-emission delivery van that met its needs, it bought a startup and developed one.}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, electric vans with a much greater range will be required to achieve the long-term goal of replacing the entire Deutsche Post and DHL Express fleet of approximately 70,000 vehicles with StreetScooter models.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/deutsche-post-dhl-makes-its-own-electric-delivery-vans/a-19332124 |title=Deutsche Post DHL makes its own electric delivery vans |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 June 2016 |website=DW |publisher=Deutsche Welle |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=Provided its StreetScooters can be produced cheaply enough compared to the alternative of buying e-vans from established auto makers, the bottom line of the world's biggest delivery services company stands to benefit from producing its own delivery vehicles - whether or not it eventually adds profits from sales of e-vans to third parties.}}</ref>\n\nThe Deutsche Post/DHL GoGreen program plans to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases and local air pollutants; the company has four interim goals for doing so, to be achieved by the year 2025. The long-term goal, summarized by Frank Appel, Chief Executive Officer, is more aggressive. \"From now until 2050, our mission will be to drive our business toward zero [logistics related] emissions. We are setting the standard for the future of the transport sector and doing our part to help the world community reach its goal of limiting global warming to less than two degrees Celsius.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpdhl.com/en/responsibility/environmental-protection/gogreen_program.html |title=2017 Deutsche Post AG Our GoGreen environmental protection program |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=8 March 2017 |website=DP DHL |publisher=Deutsche Post |access-date=26 March 2017 |quote=By the year 2050 we want to reduce all logistics-related emissions to zero \u2013 a highly ambitious goal. To ensure progress towards the 2050 zero-emissions target, we have set four interim goals to be achieved by the year 2025.}}</ref>\n\n[[BYD Auto|BYD]] supplies DHL with electric distribution fleet of commercial [[BYD T3]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bydeurope.com/news/news.php?action=readnews&page=3&nid=216|title=BYD supplies DHL with electric distribution fleet|author=bydeurope.com|publisher=bydeurope.com|date=2016-01-15|accessdate=2016-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719233328/http://www.bydeurope.com/news/news.php?action=readnews&page=3&nid=216|archive-date=19 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==DHL aviation==\n{{Main|DHL Aviation}}\n[[File:HP-1810DAE (7010604717) (3).jpg|thumb|DHL Aero Expreso Boeing 757-200F]]\nDeutsche Post owns five airline subsidiaries operating for DHL Express, operating approx. 250 aircraft and another 21 aircraft on orders, which are collectively referred to as [[DHL Aviation]]. DHL Express is an equal partner in a sixth airline that operates for DHL Express:\n* '''[[Blue Dart Aviation]]''', [[Chennai]], [[India]], provides services for Indian destinations from [[Chennai International Airport]]\n* '''[[DHL Aero Expreso]]''', [[Panama City]], [[Panama]] provides services for destinations in Central and South America\n* '''[[DHL Air UK]]''', [[Hounslow]], [[United Kingdom]] provides services for European destinations from [[East Midlands Airport]]\n* '''[[European Air Transport Leipzig]]''', [[Leipzig]], [[Germany]] provides services for European destinations from [[Leipzig/Halle Airport]]\n* '''[[AeroLogic]]''' (''joint venture with [[Lufthansa]]''), [[Schkeuditz]], [[Germany]] provides services from Europe to central and eastern Asian destinations from Leipzig/Halle Airport and [[Frankfurt Airport]]\n* '''[[DHL International Aviation ME|SNAS/DHL]]''', [[Bahrain]] provides services for [[Middle East]] destinations from [[Bahrain International Airport]]\n\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Pair of RS Spyders.jpg|thumb|DHL-colored [[Team Penske]] [[Porsche RS Spyder]] LMP2 racing cars of [[Penske Racing]]]]\nFor several years, DHL was the primary sponsor of the [[Porsche RS Spyder]] [[Le Mans Prototype]]s in the [[International Motor Sports Association]] [[American Le Mans Series]]. DHL also sponsors [[Ryan Hunter-Reay]]'s #28 [[IndyCar Series]] car for [[Andretti Autosport]] since 2011. With DHL, Hunter-Reay won the championship for the [[2012 IndyCar Series season]] as well as the [[2014 Indianapolis 500]]. DHL were the main title sponsor of the [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] [[Formula One]] team during [[2002 Formula One season|2002]]. Since then, DHL has become a regular track-side sponsor at various races throughout each year, as well as becoming the 'Official Logistics Partner' of the sport. Since 2007, they also sponsor the [[DHL Fastest Lap Award]] for the driver that achieves the most fastest laps in a season.<ref>{{cite news| url =http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/642713/dhl-sponsor-formula-1s-fastest-laps-trophy/| title = DHL to sponsor Formula 1's fastest laps trophy| publisher = Brand Republic| accessdate = 16 November 2015}}</ref> \n[[File:Jordan GP 2002 sato.jpg|thumb|A [[Jordan Grand Prix]] Formula One car with a DHL paint scheme at the US Grand Prix at the Indianapolis track.]]\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United Football Club]] announced them as their first training kit sponsor in August 2011, agreeing to a four-year deal with DHL reported to be worth \u00a340&nbsp;million; it is believed to be the first instance of training kit sponsorship in English football.<ref>{{cite news |title=DHL delivers new shirt deal |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Club-News/2011/Aug/DHL-delivers-ground-breaking-deal.aspx |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United unveils two new commercial deals |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-14615711 |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref> In 2014, [[FC Bayern Munich]] agreed to a six-year sponsorship deal with DHL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.de/en/news/news/2014/fcb-and-dhl-announce-partnership-220814.php|title=FCB and DHL announce partnership - FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen AG|work=FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen AG}}</ref> In 2012, the company became the main sponsor of [[League of Ireland]] club [[Bohemian F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.extratime.ie/newsdesk/articles/7567/|title=Bohs agree sponsorship deal with DHL - Extratime.ie - League of Ireland|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313020048/http://extratime.ie/newsdesk/articles/7567/|archivedate=2012-03-13}}</ref>\n\nDHL is the current title sponsor of the South African Western Cape Rugby Union teams [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] and the [[Stormers]]. This is came into effect on 1 January 2011 for a period of three years.<ref name=\"stormers_sponsorship\">{{cite web|url=http://thestormers.com/dhl-new-sponsor-for-wp-stormers-rugby/ |title=DHL new sponsor for WP/ Stormers Rugby |publisher=The Stormers |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> DHL are still the current sponsor for both teams as of the 2017/18 season.\n\nFor the [[2011\u201312 Volvo Ocean Race]] DHL was one of four race partners providing logistics for this event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.volvooceanrace.com/en/partners/4_DHL.html|title=Volvo Ocean Race|author=Volvo Ocean Race|work=Volvo Ocean Race|access-date=21 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125182003/http://www.volvooceanrace.com/en/partners/4_DHL.html|archive-date=25 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>And AFC Champions league Official Timing and Logistics Partner</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the company is sponsoring, with IMG Fashion, ''DHL Exported'', which is aimed at \"assisting designers who are already successful locally to gain momentum internationally\".<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/a-global-boost-7409299?src=nl/mornReport/20140205 | title=DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers | publisher=WWD | date=5 February 2014 | accessdate=5 February 2014 | author=Lockwood, Lisa}}</ref> DHL Exported will \"sponsor a chosen designer for two consecutive seasons at\" the Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week in New York, London Fashion Week, Milan Fashion Week or Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week Tokyo.<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\"/> IMG Fashion \"will accept applications from February 17 through April 2 at {{URL|dhlexported.com}}\".<ref name=\"DHL, IMG Fashion Launch Program to Boost Designers\"/>\n\nExpanding its support to various cultural endeavors, DHL signed as the Official Logistics partner for Cirque du Soleil. DHL transports up to 2,000 tonnes and 80 freight containers utilizing air, sea, and land to transport the equipment from one city to the next.<ref>[https://www.dhl.com/en/about_us/partnerships/music_and_arts/cirque_du_soleil.html DHL. \"Partnerships: Cirque du Soleil.\" Retrieved June 20, 2016]</ref>\n \nIn 2015 DHL became the main sponsor of Italian volleyball club [[Modena Volley]], covering the whole men's [[Italian Volleyball League|SuperLega Italian championship]] and the [[CEV Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/fridays_daily_deal_round_up_love_raina_and_mor | title=Friday's Daily Deal round-up: Love, Raina and more| publisher=SportsProMedia | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=8 October 2015 | author=Kennedy, Mike}}</ref>\n\nDHL is a major sponsor of [[Surf Life Saving Australia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sls.com.au/partners/|title=Partners - Surf Life Saving|newspaper=Surf Life Saving|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n\n* In 2002, [[2002 \u00dcberlingen mid-air collision|Bashkirian Airlines Flight 2937]], a [[Tupolev Tu-154]] passenger jet, collided with DHL Flight 611, a [[Boeing 757#757-200|Boeing 757-200]] cargo jet at {{convert|35000|ft|m|abbr=on}} over [[\u00dcberlingen]], Germany. All 69 passengers on board the Bashkiran flight (consisting mainly of Russian schoolchildren) and the two pilots of DHL were killed.<ref name=\"PCI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/2002/2002-38.htm|title=Information regarding the air accident|author=PlaneCrashInfo.com|accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref name=\"AD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=07012002&reg=RA-85816&airline=Bashkirian+Airlines|title=Information regarding the air accident|author=AirDisaster.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228171058/http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=07012002&reg=RA-85816&airline=Bashkirian+Airlines|archivedate=2014-02-28|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\n* In 22 November 2003, [[2003 Baghdad DHL attempted shootdown incident|DHL shootdown incident in Baghdad]] wherein Iraqi insurgents fired an [[9K32 Strela-2|SA-7 \"Grail\"]] [[surface-to-air missile]] at a [[European Air Transport]] [[Airbus A300]] operating on behalf of DHL. The aircraft took off from [[Baghdad]] airport whereupon the missile struck the left wing, disabling all three [[Hydraulic drive system|hydraulic systems]] and set the wing on fire. The aircraft began a dangerous [[phugoid]] (vertical oscillation) but the crew managed to land safely at the airport, despite only being able to control the aircraft by adjusting the engine thrust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightsafety.org/citations/dhl_cit.html|title=DHL|author=Flight Safety|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505001324/http://www.flightsafety.org/citations/dhl_cit.html|archivedate=May 5, 2008|accessdate=2008-10-31}}</ref>\n*In October 2008, two DHL Express Middle East senior executives, David Giles and Jason Bresler, were assassinated in Kabul, by one of their own Afghan employees; they received military honors by the U.S. military, the first of such kind in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Story.asp?Article=233511&Sn=BNEW&IssueID=31228%7ctitle=Gulf-daily-news.com%7cpublisher=|title=Gulf Daily News \u00bb Local News \u00bb DHL official is mourned|work=gulf-daily-news.com}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2010, A DHL [[Antonov An-26]] aircraft made an emergency landing on the frozen [[Lake \u00dclemiste]], close to [[Tallinn Airport|Lennart Meri Tallinn Airport]]. Initial reports indicated problems with the landing gear and one of the engines. The flight was operated by [[Exin]] on behalf of DHL. The aircraft involved was SP-FDO and the flight departed from Helsinki Airport. Two of the six crew members were injured.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[DHL Balloon]]\n* [[Major League Baseball Reliever of the Year Award#Delivery Man Award (2005\u20132013)|Delivery Man Award (2005\u20132013)]]\n* [[DHL Fastest Lap Award]]\n*[[Wilmington, Ohio]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dhl.com}}\n* [http://www.globalaviationresource.com/reports/2009/dhlhubeastmidlands.php Major DHL Express feature on Global Aviation Resource]\n\n{{Deutsche Post}}\n{{British Royal Warrant holders}}\n{{Trucking industry in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:DHL Express ]]\n[[Category:Express mail]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Logistics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1969]]\n[[Category:British Royal Warrant holders]]\n[[Category:Broward County, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "91.212.36.250", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DHL"}
{"title_page": "Jakob Nacken", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jakob Nacken\n| image         = File:Nacken post card 1935.jpg\n| caption       = Ripley's Odditorium 1935\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = February 15, 1906\n| birth_place   = D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany\n| death_date    = March 29, 1987 (age 81)\n| death_place   = Europe\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = German\n| occupation    = {{unbulleted list| sideshow artist|circus performer   }}\n| other_names   = {{unbulleted list| \"Uranus\" |World's Tallest Man |Giant from Rhineland }}\n| salary        = \n| networth      = \n| height        = 7 ft 3 in\n| weight        = \n| term          = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| party         = \n| boards        = \n| religion      = \n| spouse        = Maria\n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Jakob Hudson Nacken''' or '''Jacob Nacken''' (February 15, 1906&nbsp;{{ndash}} March 29, 1987) was a German [[Freak show|circus curiosity]] and advertising medium who performed in Europe and the United States. He began his career while a teenager as an exceptionally tall person performing as a giant in a traveling circus. He appeared in the [[1939 New York World's Fair]]. Nacken was the largest soldier in the [[German Army (1935\u20131945)|German Army]] during [[World War II]] at a height of {{convert|7|ft|3|in|spell=in}}. He was employed as a giant [[Santa Claus]] by U.S. companies and organizations during the month of December. He appeared on American television as a figure of high stature and in freak shows as the World's Tallest Man. He married a normal-size person.\n\n== Early life ==\nNacken was born in [[D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany]], on February 15, 1906.<ref name=LooksUpTo>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Looks Up To |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46638708/ |work= The Morning Call | page= 28 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 17 February 1950 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Both his parents were {{convert|6|ft|2|in|spell=in}}. His sister Josephine was {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|spell=in}} tall; his two-years-younger brother Wilhelm grew to be {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|spell=in}} tall; his other brother, who was eight years younger than Nacken, became {{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|spell=in}}.<ref name=Ridgewood>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ridgewood Woman Recognizes Photo of Captive Brother |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46042548/ |work= The Morning Call | page= 20 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 16 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Mid-life and career ==\nNacken began his career in show business performing as \"Uranus\" and the \"giant from the Rhineland\" in a German traveling circus. He appeared at [[Luna Park, Paris|Luna Park]], an amusement park in Paris, in 1922. Nacken was internationally known for his height of {{convert|7|ft|3|in|m|spell=in}} and earned an engagement at the 1939 New York World's Fair.<ref name=GermanGiantCaprured>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= German Giant captured at Calais |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46034837/ |work= The Daily News | page=14 |location=Davenport, Iowa|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Germany at the beginning of [[World War II]] and was immediately drafted into the German Army, becoming their tallest soldier ever.<ref name=Big_OR_small>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Big or Small, They Fall |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46611910/ |work= Daily Republican Register| page= 1 |location=Mount Carmel, Illinois|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=X_X_X>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Bigger They are x x x |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46612383/ |work= Arizona Republic | page= 8 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |date= 9 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=AmazingExploits>{{cite web |url= https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/11254826.video-amazing-exploits-of-d-day-veteran-bob-roberts-the-second-man-to-set-foot-on-juno-beach/ |title= Amazing exploits of D-Day veteran Bob Roberts, the second man to set foot on Juno beach |accessdate=March 14, 2020|quote= }}</ref> Nacken was put into a gun crew with 250 soldiers who were captured at [[Juno Beach]] in [[Normandy]], France, in August 1944.<ref name=TallGermanGiant>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Some Germans Come Tall |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46037314/ |work= Austin American-Statesman | page= 2 |location=Austin, Texas|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=CaptureJunoBeach>{{cite web |url= https://twnews.co.uk/uk-news/pint-sized-hero-infantryman-who-frisked-giant-7ft-3in-german-soldier-on-juno-beach-on-d-day |title= Pint-sized hero infantryman who frisked giant 7ft 3in German soldier on Juno beach on D-Day |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote= }}</ref> British Corporal Bob Roberts ({{convert|5|ft|3|in|m}}), who commanded a troop of seven men, captured the gun crew.<ref name=MysteryGermanyGiant>{{cite web |url= https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/8216165.former-circus-giant-jakob-nacken-identified-as-mystery-germany-soldier/ |title= Former circus giant Jakob Nacken identified as mystery Germany soldier |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote= }}</ref> Nacken and his men were taken to England as [[Prisoners of War|prisoners of war]] and remained there until the end of the war.<ref name=MysteryGermanyGiant/><ref name=KingSizeSleeper/>\n\nIn August 1949, newspapers announced Nacken was to return to the United States because he wanted to leave post-war Germany.<ref name=EuropeanGiant>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Famous European Giant to Become Resident Here |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46528317/ |work= The News| page= 27 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 5 August 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken's sister prepared a place for him and his wife to live in [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref name=PatersonNewsPart2>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= European Giant to Become Resident Here |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46526720/ |work= The News| page = 2 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 5 August 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken and his wife emigrated to the United States on ''[[SS Atlantic]]'' from [[Genoa|Genoa, Italy]],<ref name=LooksUpTo/> arriving in the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|port of New York City]] December 6, 1950.<ref name=LooksUpTo/><ref name=Jack&Jill>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= \"Jake\" and Jills |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46036721 |work= The Muscatine Journal| page= 16 |location=Muscatine, Iowa|date= 14 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\nNacken sought work that would suit his stature. Through newspaper pictures and [[Path\u00e9 News|Path\u00e9 newsreels]], he was well-known to the people of the United States. For the month of December 1949, he worked as a giant Santa Claus for companies and organizations.<ref name=SantaTop>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Santa's Tops |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46034687/ |work= Visalia Times-Delta| page=20 |location=Visalia, California|date=17 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=NackenSantaGroomed>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Old St. Nicholas Gets Around |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46036140/ |work= Statesville Daily Record| page= 16 |location=Statesville, North Carolina|date= 25 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Children were able to walk between Nacken's legs<ref name=KingSizeSanta>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= King-Size Santa |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46035425/ |work= The Berkshire Eagle| page=3 |location=Pittsfield, Massachusetts|date= 8 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=WalkUnder>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Biggest Santa |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46040073 |work= Lancaster Eagle-Gazette| page= 10 |location=Lancaster, Ohio|date= 13 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> and he was dubbed the world's tallest Santa.<ref name=WorldTallestSanta>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Santas Tops |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46561621 |work= The Chillicothe Constitution| page=24 |location=Chillicothe, Missouri|date= 23 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=GiantCitizen/> Nacken worked in ''[[Ripley's Believe It or Not!]]'' shows as the \"World's Tallest Man\".<ref name=RinglingSeason>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Out of Circus, Paterson Giant Seeks Employment |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45994425 |work= The News| page =40 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date=8 December 1950 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> He appeared on several television shows as a celebrity known as \"Germany's Long Jake\".<ref name=LongJakeNacken>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= \"Long Jake\" to Arrive Today |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46037775/ |work= The News | page= 3 |location= Paterson, New Jersey|date= 6 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn August 10, 1927, Nacken married Maria from [[Kematen an der Ybbs|Kematen an der Ybbs, Austria]], in [[Brussels, Belgium]].<ref name=LooksUpTo/> She stood {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|spell=in}} tall.<ref name=RinglingSeason/> He became a citizen of the United States on December 16, 1955.<ref name=GiantCitizen>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= 'World's Tallest Santa' Looks To Uncle Sam For Christmas Gift |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46582616/ |work= Public Opinion| page = 4 |location=Chambersburg, Pennsylvania|date=15 December 1955 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken wore size 17 boots as an adult.<ref name=KingSizeSleeper>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Easier To Stand Than Sleep Says King-Size Ex-Soldier |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46040801 |work= The Gazette| page = 21 |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada|date=11 April 1956 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> He was called Germany's tallest man<ref name=GermanyTallestMan>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Germany's tallest man visits Oakland's littlest house! |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46585093/ |work= Oakland Tribune| page = 33 |location=Oakland, California|date=18 October 1951 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=TallestBouncer>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Giant \"Bouncer\" Effective. |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46611670/ |work= Hartford Courant| page = 19 |location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=12 August 1929 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> and was credited as being the world's tallest man at the time.{{sfn|Candlewick|2018|page=191}}{{sfn|Yonke|2015|page=19}} He had bruises on his head from hitting the tops of doorways that were built to accommodate people of normal height.<ref name=GiantAmericanCitizen>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Where'd We Put The Binoculars? |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46584393 |work= York Daily Record| page = 15 |location=York, Pennsylvania|date=1 June 1953 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Later life and death ==\nNacken's last appearance as \"World's Tallest Man\" was in 1959 at [[Ripley's Odditorium]] on [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway, New York City]]. He died in Europe at age 81.<ref name=GiantDeath>{{cite web |url= https://www.genesis6giants.com/index.php?s=549 |title= Genis 6 Giants |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote= }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=285px heights=285px>\nFile:Jakob Nacken age16.jpg|Jakob Nacken at age 16 in 1922\nFile:Schaefer's circus 1924.jpg|Nacken 17 as circus acrobat <br> with a young boy assistant\nFile:UraniusName1924.jpg| Jakob Nacken 1924 at age 18\nFile:Nacken as Uranus.jpg|Nacken in German circus <br>as \"Uranus\" at age 19\nFile:Nacken 21 years old Paris.jpg|Jakob Nacken 21 years old Paris\nFile:Tallgerry.jpg|Nacken captured at Calais, France <br>in 1944 when he was 38 years old\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Jakob Nacken}}\n*[[Ella Ewing]]\n*[[List of tallest people]]\n*[[Robert Wadlow]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Candlewick |first= |title= Voices from Second World War| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lI9SDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA191&dq=%22Jakob+Nacken%22+world%27s+tallest&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnyL6ck5foAhVCYs0KHbudBt8Q6AEwAXoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jakob%20Nacken%22%20world's%20tallest&f=false |date= 2018|publisher= Candlewick Press|ISBN=0763697737|quote= }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Yonke |first= David |title= Lost Toledo| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=c5VoCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA19&dq=%22Jakob+Nacken%22+world%27s+tallest&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnyL6ck5foAhVCYs0KHbudBt8Q6AEwAHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jakob%20Nacken%22%20world's%20tallest&f=false |date= 2015|publisher= Arcadia Publishing|ISBN=1625850980|quote= }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nacken, Jakob}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American circus performers]]\n[[Category:German circus performers]]\n[[Category:People with gigantism]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jakob Nacken\n| image         = File:Nacken post card 1935.jpg\n| caption       = Ripley's Odditorium 1935\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = February 15, 1906\n| birth_place   = D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany\n| death_date    = March 29, 1987 (age 81)\n| death_place   = Europe\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = German\n| occupation    = {{unbulleted list| sideshow artist|circus performer   }}\n| other_names   = {{unbulleted list| \"Uranus\" |World's Tallest Man |Giant from Rhineland }}\n| salary        = \n| networth      = \n| height        = 7 ft 3 in\n| weight        = \n| term          = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| party         = \n| boards        = \n| religion      = \n| spouse        = Maria\n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Jakob Hudson Nacken''' or '''Jacob Nacken''' (February 15, 1906 {{ndash}} March 29, 1987) was a German [[Freak show|circus curiosity]] and advertising medium who performed in Europe and the United States. He began his career while a teenager as an exceptionally tall person performing as a giant in a traveling circus. He appeared in the [[1939 New York World's Fair]]. Nacken was the largest soldier in the [[German Army (1935\u20131945)|German Army]] during [[World War II]] at a height of {{convert|7|ft|3|in|spell=in}}. He was employed as a giant [[Santa Claus]] by U.S. companies and organizations during the month of December. He appeared on American television as a figure of high stature and in freak shows as the World's Tallest Man. He married a normal size person.\n\n== Early life ==\nNacken was born in [[D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany]], on February 15, 1906.<ref name=LooksUpTo>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Looks Up To |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46638708/ |work= The Morning Call | page= 28 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 17 February 1950 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Both his parents were {{convert|6|ft|2|in|spell=in}}. His sister Josephine was {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|spell=in}} tall; his two-years-younger brother Wilhelm grew to be {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|spell=in}} tall; his other brother, who was eight years younger than Nacken, became {{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|spell=in}}.<ref name=Ridgewood>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ridgewood Woman Recognizes Photo of Captive Brother  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46042548/ |work= The Morning Call | page= 20 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 16 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Mid-life and career ==\nNacken began his career in show business performing as \"Uranus\" and the \"giant from the Rhineland\" in a German traveling circus. He appeared at [[Luna Park, Paris|Luna Park]], an amusement park in Paris, in 1922. Nacken was internationally known for his height of {{convert|7|ft|3|in|m|spell=in}} and earned an engagement at the 1939 New York World's Fair.<ref name=GermanGiantCaprured>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= German Giant captured at Calais  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46034837/ |work= The Daily News | page=14 |location=Davenport, Iowa|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Germany at the beginning of [[World War II]] and was immediately drafted into the German Army, becoming their tallest soldier ever.<ref name=Big_OR_small>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Big or Small, They Fall  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46611910/ |work= Daily Republican Register| page= 1 |location=Mount Carmel, Illinois|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=X_X_X>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Bigger They are x x x  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46612383/ |work= Arizona Republic | page= 8 |location=Phoenix, Arizona |date= 9 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=AmazingExploits>{{cite web |url= https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/11254826.video-amazing-exploits-of-d-day-veteran-bob-roberts-the-second-man-to-set-foot-on-juno-beach/ |title= Amazing exploits of D-Day veteran Bob Roberts, the second man to set foot on Juno beach |accessdate=March 14, 2020|quote=  }}</ref> Nacken was put into a gun crew with 250 soldiers who were captured at [[Juno Beach]] in [[Normandy]], France, in August 1944.<ref name=TallGermanGiant>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Some Germans Come Tall  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46037314/ |work= Austin American-Statesman | page= 2 |location=Austin, Texas|date= 4 October 1944 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=CaptureJunoBeach>{{cite web |url= https://twnews.co.uk/uk-news/pint-sized-hero-infantryman-who-frisked-giant-7ft-3in-german-soldier-on-juno-beach-on-d-day |title= Pint-sized hero infantryman who frisked giant 7ft 3in German soldier on Juno beach on D-Day |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=  }}</ref> British Corporal Bob Roberts ({{convert|5|ft|3|in|m}}), who commanded a troop of seven men, captured the gun crew.<ref name=MysteryGermanyGiant>{{cite web |url= https://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/8216165.former-circus-giant-jakob-nacken-identified-as-mystery-germany-soldier/ |title= Former circus giant Jakob Nacken identified as mystery Germany soldier |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=  }}</ref> Nacken and his men were taken to England as [[Prisoners of War|prisoners of war]] and remained there until the end of the war.<ref name=MysteryGermanyGiant/><ref name=KingSizeSleeper/>\n\nIn August 1949, newspapers announced Nacken was to return to the United States because he wanted to leave post-war Germany.<ref name=EuropeanGiant>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Famous European Giant to Become Resident Here |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46528317/  |work= The News| page= 27 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 5 August 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken's sister prepared a place for him and his wife to live in [[Paterson, New Jersey]].<ref name=PatersonNewsPart2>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= European Giant to Become Resident Here  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46526720/ |work= The News| page = 2 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date= 5 August 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken and his wife emigrated to the United States on ''[[SS Atlantic]]'' from [[Genoa|Genoa, Italy]],<ref name=LooksUpTo/> arriving in the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|port of New York City]] December 6, 1950.<ref name=LooksUpTo/><ref name=Jack&Jill>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= \"Jake\" and Jills  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46036721 |work=  The Muscatine Journal| page= 16 |location=Muscatine, Iowa|date= 14 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\nNacken sought work that would suit his stature. Through newspaper pictures and [[Path\u00e9 News|Path\u00e9 newsreels]], he was well-known to the people of the United States. For the month of December 1949, he worked as a giant Santa Claus for companies and organizations.<ref name=SantaTop>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Santa's Tops  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46034687/ |work= Visalia Times-Delta| page=20 |location=Visalia, California|date=17 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=NackenSantaGroomed>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Old St. Nicholas Gets Around  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46036140/  |work=  Statesville Daily Record| page= 16 |location=Statesville, North Carolina|date= 25 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Children were able to walk between Nacken's legs<ref name=KingSizeSanta>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= King-Size Santa  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46035425/ |work= The Berkshire Eagle| page=3 |location=Pittsfield, Massachusetts|date= 8 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=WalkUnder>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Biggest Santa |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46040073 |work= Lancaster Eagle-Gazette| page= 10 |location=Lancaster, Ohio|date= 13 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> and he was dubbed the world's tallest Santa.<ref name=WorldTallestSanta>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Santas Tops  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46561621  |work= The Chillicothe Constitution| page=24 |location=Chillicothe, Missouri|date= 23 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=GiantCitizen/> Nacken worked in ''[[Ripley's Believe It or Not!]]'' shows as the \"World's Tallest Man\".<ref name=RinglingSeason>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Out of Circus, Paterson Giant Seeks Employment  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45994425 |work= The News| page =40 |location=Paterson, New Jersey|date=8 December 1950 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> He appeared on several television shows as a celebrity known as \"Germany's Long Jake\".<ref name=LongJakeNacken>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= \"Long Jake\" to Arrive Today  |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46037775/ |work= The News | page= 3 |location= Paterson, New Jersey|date= 6 December 1949 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn August 10, 1927, Nacken married Maria from [[Kematen an der Ybbs|Kematen an der Ybbs, Austria]], in [[Brussels, Belgium]].<ref name=LooksUpTo/> She stood {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|spell=in}} tall.<ref name=RinglingSeason/> He became a citizen of the United States on December 16, 1955.<ref name=GiantCitizen>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= 'World's Tallest Santa' Looks To Uncle Sam For Christmas Gift |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46582616/ |work= Public Opinion| page = 4 |location=Chambersburg, Pennsylvania|date=15 December 1955 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Nacken wore size 17 boots as an adult.<ref name=KingSizeSleeper>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Easier To Stand Than Sleep Says King-Size Ex-Soldier |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46040801 |work= The Gazette| page = 21 |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada|date=11 April 1956 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> He was called Germany's tallest man<ref name=GermanyTallestMan>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Germany's tallest man visits Oakland's littlest house! |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46585093/ |work= Oakland Tribune| page = 33 |location=Oakland, California|date=18 October 1951 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref><ref name=TallestBouncer>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Giant \"Bouncer\" Effective. |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46611670/ |work= Hartford Courant| page = 19 |location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=12 August 1929 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> and was credited as being the world's tallest man at the time.{{sfn|Candlewick|2018|page=191}}{{sfn|Yonke|2015|page=19}} He had bruises on his head from hitting the tops of doorways that were built to accommodate people of normal height.<ref name=GiantAmericanCitizen>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Where'd We Put The Binoculars? |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46584393 |work= York Daily Record| page = 15 |location=York, Pennsylvania|date=1 June 1953 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Later life and death ==\nNacken's last appearance as \"World's Tallest Man\" was in 1959 at [[Ripley's Odditorium]] on [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway, New York City]]. He died in Europe at age 81.<ref name=GiantDeath>{{cite web |url= https://www.genesis6giants.com/index.php?s=549 |title= Genis 6 Giants |accessdate=March 12, 2020|quote=  }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=285px heights=285px>\nFile:Jakob Nacken age16.jpg|Jakob Nacken at age 16 in 1922\nFile:Schaefer's circus 1924.jpg|Nacken 17 as circus acrobat <br> with a young boy assistant\nFile:UraniusName1924.jpg| Jakob Nacken 1924 at age 18\nFile:Nacken as Uranus.jpg|Nacken in German circus <br>as \"Uranus\" at age 19\nFile:Nacken 21 years old Paris.jpg|Jakob Nacken 21 years old Paris\nFile:Tallgerry.jpg|Nacken captured at Calais, France <br>in 1944 when he was 38 years old\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Jakob Nacken}}\n*[[Ella Ewing]]\n*[[Robert Wadlow]]\n*[[List of tallest people]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Candlewick |first=  |title= Voices from Second World War| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lI9SDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA191&dq=%22Jakob+Nacken%22+world%27s+tallest&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnyL6ck5foAhVCYs0KHbudBt8Q6AEwAXoECAQQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jakob%20Nacken%22%20world's%20tallest&f=false  |date= 2018|publisher= Candlewick Press|ISBN=0763697737|quote=  }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Yonke |first= David |title= Lost Toledo| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=c5VoCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA19&dq=%22Jakob+Nacken%22+world%27s+tallest&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnyL6ck5foAhVCYs0KHbudBt8Q6AEwAHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jakob%20Nacken%22%20world's%20tallest&f=false  |date= 2015|publisher= Arcadia Publishing|ISBN=1625850980|quote=  }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nacken, Jakob}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American circus performers]]\n[[Category:German circus performers]]\n[[Category:People with gigantism]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jakob_Nacken"}
{"title_page": "1909 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|reason=drop caps as per [[MOS:HEADINGS]]|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\nThe 1909 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was the league's first ever official season. It celebrated its centenary in 2009. Four representative matches had been played in 1908 as players in Auckland attempted to showcase the new code to both Auckland residents and those elsewhere.\n\n===First Meeting===\nA meeting of players was held on Monday 12 July where it was decided to call for another meeting the following Monday and to invite all interested parties to attend. The ultimate aim was to form a league. It was also stated that \"three clubs will be formed, two in the city and one at the North Shore\".<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/A Forward Movement\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14112\n| date = 14 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090714.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> The meeting was duly held on 19 July at the Chamber of Commerce on Swanson Street. Mr. A.E. Glover, M.P., occupied the chair, and there was a large attendance of around 150 supporters and players. They were to affiliate with the Northern Union and hold a practice match on the following Saturday. \"Mr. R. Eagleton offered the league the use of three suitable playing grounds in Epsom\". The ground was located near Potters Paddock which was later converted into Alexandra Racecourse.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Past Glories of the Domain/Old-Time Sports Grounds\n| page = 56\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14112\n| date = 14 July 1930\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19300507.2.199.83\n| accessdate = 12 October 2019}}</ref> Elections for officers were also held with 14 appointments made.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/Auckland Rugby Football League\n| page = 7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LXI| issue=106\n| date = 7 May 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090720.2.99.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North Shore Albions Are Formed===\nA further meeting was held at North Shore on the Wednesday evening at the Council Chambers in Devonport with 40 in attendance, and a club was formed. It was noted that they had the playing numbers for two teams and they had \"taken the pick of the amateur players of the district club\". The club would be called [[North Shore Albions]]. On the Thursday night a preliminary meeting was held in the city with 20 players attending with the goal of forming a club that was either a city team or a combination of a city and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] team, while a [[Newton Rangers|Newton club]] was also aimed to be formed the following week as there was \"considerable dissatisfaction among the members at the management of the Auckland Union\".<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/Rapid Developments/Clubs Being Formed\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14120\n| date = 23 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090723.2.106.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> It was decided to play a match on the Saturday between the [[North Shore Albions|North Shore]] team and the city team. The match was duly played between North Shore and [[City Rovers|City]] and resulted in a win to the former by 44 points to 22.\n\nChairman of the league, D.W. McLean spoke with a representative of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' and was reported as saying the following; \"no payment would be made for playing, but the men when away from home would be recompensed for lost time. They would provide players with uniforms free in order that a team might take the field in a regulation costume, not in varied coloured pants and stockings, as is often seen even in rep. Rugby matches. Their meetings would be open to the press and full information will be given to the public of all moneys received and expended...\". He \"spoke enthusiastically of the possibilities of the new code, from which he contended the rougher elements of rugby had been removed, this providing a game which was full of bright play and sparkling situations. The liability of getting hurt had been greatly reduced by the removal of scrums and line-out play\". It was also reported that several prominent players, questioned about why they had left the Rugby Union game said that \"they were tired of the unequalness of the contests under the present system. There was no sport in being beaten by 61 points to nil as the North Shore seniors were recently by the [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] team\u2026 the management of the Auckland Union was not mindful enough of the clubs\u2019 or players interests\".<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Game/Bright Play and Sparkling Situations\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14124\n| date = 28 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090728.2.11.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ponsonby United Are Born===\nAt a meeting at Leys Institute on 30 July the Ponsonby club was formed. There were 50 supporters present with Mr. A Thompson chairing the meeting. Also in attendance were Mr [[James Carlaw]], along with [[Arthur Carlaw]], [[Charles Dunning]], and [[Jack Stanaway]]. They called for another meeting to be held the following week to enroll players.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =League Football\n| page = 8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XL| issue=181\n| date = 28 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090731.2.70\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1908 Auckland Rugby League season|1908]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=1st [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=1909}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1910 Auckland Rugby League season|1910]]}}\n        {{end}}\n{{TOC right}}\n\n===Representative Matches===\n[[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] played four representative matches, though the first match was still prior to the official formation of the league. They played the New Zealand Maori team, two matches against [[Taranaki rugby league team|Taranaki]], one against Wellington, and a further match against Rotorua which was a largely junior side. The match versus Wellington on 9 October drew 4,000 spectators and raised \u00a3122 for the [[Auckland Rugby League]].\n\n======Auckland v NZ Maori======\nA match was played between [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] and a [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]] team on 10 July which was preparing to depart for a tour of [[Australia]]. The Auckland team was victorious by 21 points to 14 in front of a crowd estimated at 3,000. Proceeds from the match were to go towards the formation and establishment of the league.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/Auckland V M\u0101ori\n| page = 8\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14103\n| date = 3 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090703.2.111\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> [[Auckland City Council]] granted use of [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] for the match to be played on Saturday, 10 July. The council allowed for an admission charge \"not exceeding one shilling for each person\u2026 with an extra shilling for every horse or vehicle, and an additional charge not exceeding one shilling for each person for admission to the pavilion\".<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Corporation Notices/City of Auckland/Victoria Park\n| page = 10\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14103\n| date = 3 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090703.2.126.4\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> The Maori team was preparing for a tour of Australia.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Game/Auckland V M\u0101ori\n| page = 4\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14106\n| date = 7 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090707.2.8.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> They had been based in [[Te Kuiti]] with Barclay tutoring the side. He had been a member of the last 'native' team to tour Australia. The Auckland team was preparing hard under the guidance of W. Mackrell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football\n| page = 7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XL| issue=160\n| date = 7 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090707.2.75.1\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 10 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 21\u201314\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland v Maori Team\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14110\n| date = 12 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090712.2.99.1\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| away = NZ M\u0101ori\n| try1 = [[Charles Dunning]], [[Thomas Houghton (rugby league)|Thomas Houghton]], C Linkhorn 2, [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]\n| con1 = [[William Tyler (rugby)|William Tyler]] 2, S Marshall\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Ernie Asher|Te Keepa Pouwhiuwhiu]], [[Albert Asher]], [[Alex Stanaway|Ariki Haira]], Rewi Maniapoto\n| con2 = [[Alex Stanaway|Ariki Haira]]\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = Matt Hooper\n}}\n\n======Auckland v Taranaki======\nTaranaki tipped over the home team 8\u20137. On 31 July a trial match was played between A and B teams before [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]] selected the representative side to face Taranaki. It was an uninspiring encounter, won by the Possible selection 37\u201329.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Game/A and B Match\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XL| issue=182\n| date = 2 August 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090802.2.69\n| accessdate = 2 August 2019}}</ref> The match against Taranaki marked the first \u2018official\u2019 Auckland team as it was selected after a league had formed. \n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 7 August\n| time = 3pm\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 7\u20138\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Taranaki Beats Auckland/An Interesting Game\n| page = 7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XL| issue=188\n| date = 9 August 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090809.2.70\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| away = Taranaki\n| try1 = [[Charles Dunning]]\n| con1 = [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]\n| drop1 = Neighbour\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = T Haskell, T Smith\n| con2 = [[Arthur Hardgrave]]\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 5700\n| referee = [[Lance Todd]]\n}}\n\n======Auckland v Taranaki======\nOn 12 September a trial match was played at Eagleton's Paddock in Epsom between A and B teams. The A team won by 22 points to 8 with tries for the A team to [[Arthur Carlaw]] 2, [[Frederick Stanley Jackson|Fred Jackson]], [[William Mackrell]], [[George Seagar]], and Winters, with D Bradburn kicking 2 conversions. While for the B team Smith and Neighbour scored tries, and Neighbour kicked a conversion\n.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Game\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=XL| issue=218\n| date = 13 September 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090913.2.83\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]] then selected the team to face Taranaki in New Plymouth and they faired better this time winning by 27 points to 11.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 16 September\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Taranaki\n| score = 11\u201327\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland v Taranaki\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Taranaki Daily News| volume=LII| issue=192\n| date = 17 September 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TDN19090917.2.55\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| away = Auckland\n| try1 = C Moir, W McLean, T Smith\n| con1 = [[Arthur Hardgrave]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]], [[Arthur Carlaw]], [[Richard Wynyard]], [[Jim Griffen]], Penalty Try\n| con2 = D Bradburn 3, Neighbour\n| pen2 = D Bradburn 2\n| drop2 =D Bradburn\n| stadium = Recreation Sports Ground, New Plymouth\n| attendance = 2000\n| referee = [[Lance Todd]]\n}}\n\n======Auckland v Rotorua======\nAn Auckland XIII travelled to Rotorua to play the local side and was trounced by a much better team filled with M\u0101ori players who had represented them in Australia. The Auckland team was largely a junior side though it did feature several more experienced players such as [[Richard Wynyard]], [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]] and Neighbour. Unfortunately Ferguson broke his leg during the match and had to be taken to the local hospital. The Rotorua side featured [[Riki Papakura]] who a week later played for Auckland against Wellington.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 2 October\n| time =\n| home =Rotorua\n| score = 33\u20138\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Defeats Auckland Juniors\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14182\n| date = 4 October 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19091004.2.83.1\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| away = Auckland XIII\n| try1 = Rawson 2, Lane 2, Harp, Anderson, Thom\n| con1 = McCallum 4, Lane 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Neighbour, [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]\n| con2 = [[Richard Wynyard]]\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Rotorua\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n\n======Auckland v Wellington======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 9 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 19\u201322\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Wellington Defeats Auckland/An Exciting Finish\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=XLVI| issue=14188\n| date = 11 October 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19091011.2.103\n| accessdate = 12 December 2019}}</ref>\n| away = Wellington\n| try1 = [[Richard Wynyard]], [[Charles Dunning]], [[George Seagar]] 2, Grundy\n| con1 = [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]], [[William Tyler (rugby)|William Tyler]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[James Barber (rugby)|James Barber]], Cross, [[Bumper Wright]] 3, O\u2019Sullivan\n| con2 = [[James Barber (rugby)|James Barber]]\n| pen2 =\n| drop2 = Jackson\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance = 4000\n| referee = S Houghton\n}}\n\n===Auckland representative matches played and scorers===\nThe following list includes the four legitimate representative matches against New Zealand Maori, Taranaki (two matches), and Wellington. The [[Rotorua]] match is omitted as it was an Auckland Junior/Auckland XIII selection.\n\n===Auckland Representative Matches Played and Scorers===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Name!!Club!!Play!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Mark!!Points\n|-\n|1||[[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]||North Shore Albions||4||2||2||-||-||10\n|-\n|1||D Bradburn||Newton Rangers||1||-||3||2||-||10\n|-\n|3||[[Charles Dunning (rugby)|Charles Dunning]]||Ponsonby United||3||3||-||-||-||9\n|-\n|4||[[William Tyler (rugby)|William Tyler]]||Ponsonby United||3||-||3||-||-||6\n|-\n|4||C Linkhorn||City Rovers||2||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|4||[[Richard Wynyard]]||North Shore Albions||4||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|4||[[George Seagar]]||North Shore Albions||3||2||-||-||-||6\n|-\n|8||F Neighbour||North Shore Albions||3||-||1||1||-||4\n|-\n|9||[[Thomas Houghton (rugby league)|Thomas Houghton]]||Newton Rangers||1||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|9||[[Jim Griffen|Jim Griffin]]||North Shore Albions||4||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|9||[[Arthur Carlaw]]||Ponsonby United||2||1||-||-||-||3\n|-\n|9||Grundy||?||1||1||-||-||