{"title_page": "Laura Whitmore", "text_new": "{{Short description|Irish presenter and actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laura Whitmore\n| image              = Jaguar XE - Arrival in London (15185880955) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Whitmore in 2014\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1985|05|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| nationality        = Irish\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Presenter|actress}}\n| years_active       = 2008\u2013present\n| education          = [[Dublin City University]]\n| partner            = [[Iain Stirling]] (engaged)\n| website            = {{URL|http://laurawhitmore.com}}\n}}\n'''Laura Whitmore''' (born 4 May 1985)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://capitalfm.com/news/celebrity/laura-whitmore-tv-host-boyfriend-iain-stirling/|title=Who Is Laura Whitmore? Meet New Winter Love Island Host Dating Iain I Stirling|date=20 December 2019|work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital]]}}</ref> is an Irish presenter and actress, known for presenting ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]'' and ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]''. In January 2020, Whitmore began presenting ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]'' and its spinoff series, ''[[Love Island: Aftersun]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nLaura Whitmore was born in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>https://twitter.com/thewhitmore/status/1172941403074310145</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/independent-woman/celebrity-news-gossip/laura-whitmore-i-cant-stand-still-not-for-a-second-3081169.html|title=Laura Whitmore: I can't stand still, not for a second |accessdate=28 August 2012|newspaper=The Irish Independent|date=15 April 2012}}</ref> She has two half brothers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rodgers|first=Kathryn|title=Babe Laura Whitmore moves in with Coronas star|url=http://www.clickonline.com/gossip/babe-laura-whitmore-moves-in-with-coronas-star/6712/|accessdate=28 August 2012|newspaper=Irish Tatler|date=14 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619015109/http://www.clickonline.com/gossip/babe-laura-whitmore-moves-in-with-coronas-star/6712|archivedate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Whitmore attended Loreto Bray, where she was awarded Culture Student of the Year upon graduating, before attending [[Dublin City University]] where she studied journalism, including a year studying abroad at [[Boston University]] in the United States. In 2003, Whitmore was a contestant in a modelling talent search on RT\u00c9's ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'' with [[Pat Kenny]], reaching the final 15 of the competition.<ref>https://www.her.ie/entertainment/laura-whitmore-unrecognisable-photo-modelling-days-374250</ref>\nShe lives in [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], north London, as of 2018.<ref>https://irishtimes.com/life-and-style/home-and-property/interiors/at-home-with-laura-whitmore-i-love-my-records-most-1.3078220{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Television===\nIn April 2008, [[MTV Networks Europe]] launched a campaign ''Pick Me MTV''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/laura-whitmore |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831082708/http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/laura-whitmore |archivedate=31 August 2009 }}</ref> where Whitmore battled it out against other contestants to become the face of [[MTV News]] in [[MTV Europe]]. Between 2008 and 2015, she hosted news bulletins for MTV in Ireland, the UK and pan-European MTV channels. She was regularly seen on MTV News hosting special events in Ireland and elsewhere in Europe.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/fashion/2008/1125/whitmorel.html \"My Style with Laura Whitmore\"]. Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann, 25 November 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614112652/http://www.rte.ie/fashion/2008/1125/whitmorel.html |date=14 June 2010 }}</ref> \n\nFor 5 series from 2011, Whitmore hosted ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]'' on [[ITV2]] airing immediately after ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]'' .<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s100/im-a-celebrity-uk/news/a348407/im-a-celebrity-return-date-confirmed-by-itv.html |title='I'm A Celebrity' return date confirmed by ITV |work=[[Digital Spy]] |first=Alex |last=Fletcher |date=31 October 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> Whitmore announced on 14 April 2016 that she had decided to leave the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker |first=Danny |url=http://mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/im-celebrity-presenter-laura-whitmore-7758971 |title=I'm A Celebrity presenter Laura Whitmore QUITS jungle spin-off after five years saying it was a '&#39;tough decision'&#39; \u2013 Mirror Online |website=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, Whitmore appeared on [[Miriam O'Callaghan (media personality)|Miriam O'Callaghan]]'s show ''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' after carrying the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] torch.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0713/thesaturdaynightshow.html |title=Laura Whitmore joins Miriam on Saturday |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715043314/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0713/thesaturdaynightshow.html |archivedate=15 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA [[pilot episode]] of songwriting-based talent show ''[[The Hit (Irish TV series)|The Hit]]'' aired in September 2012 on [[RT\u00c9 Two]], hosted by Whitmore. On 15 March 2013, RT\u00c9 announced that the show had been ordered for a full series which was broadcast in the summer, but Whitmore would not host due to conflicting schedule in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0315/444025-thehit/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107174715/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0315/444025-thehit/ |archivedate= 7 January 2014 }}</ref> [[Aidan Power]] and [[Nicky Byrne]] presented the full series.\n\nIn April 2014, Whitmore co-hosted the ''[[11th Irish Film & Television Awards]]'' with [[Simon Delaney]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/simon-delaney-laura-whitmore-iftas-host-2014/| work= evoke.ie| title= Red carpet ready! Laura Whitmore confirmed to host the IFTA Awards with Simon Delaney| date= 13 March 2014| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121842/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/simon-delaney-laura-whitmore-iftas-host-2014/| archive-date= 17 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-says-she-cant-wait-to-co-host-the-iftas/| work=  evoke.ie| title=  Laura Whitmore talks to EVOKE.ie at the VOICE and says she can't wait to co-host the IFTAs with actor Simon Delaney| date=  23 March 2014| access-date=  17 February 2015| archive-url=  https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121327/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-says-she-cant-wait-to-co-host-the-iftas/| archive-date=  17 February 2015| url-status=  dead| df=  dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/you-live-and-learn-why-laura-whitmore-wont-dwell-on-iftas-and-the-technical-hitches-that-beset-the-awards-show/| work=  evoke.ie| title=  'You live and learn' \u2013 Why Laura Whitmore won't dwell on IFTAs and the technical hitches that beset the awards show| date=  5 May 2014| access-date=  17 February 2015| archive-url=  https://web.archive.org/web/20150217120449/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/you-live-and-learn-why-laura-whitmore-wont-dwell-on-iftas-and-the-technical-hitches-that-beset-the-awards-show/| archive-date=  17 February 2015| url-status=  dead| df=  dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Whitmore joined the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest|BBC Eurovision]] team as a commentator for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014]] semi-finals in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark alongside [[Scott Mills]] on [[BBC Three]]. She replaced [[Ana Matronic]] in the role,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/laura-adds-more-irish-sparkle-to-bbcs-eurovision-song-show-30157711.html|title=Laura adds more Irish sparkle to BBC's eurovision song show|publisher=Herald.ie|date=5 April 2014|accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref> but did not return in 2015. In 2014, she was an occasional presenter of \"The Hub\" section on ITV's ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''.\n\nOn 24 October 2014, Whitmore appeared in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night]]'' to raise awareness of testicular cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4043842/fullcredits/|title=The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night (2014 TV Movie) : Full Cast & Crew|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Whitmore announced that she was leaving MTV News after seven years presenting on the TV Channel, but would continue to present irregular segments and specials.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-leaving-mtv-news-statement/| work= evoke.ie| title= 'It's time to hang up my MTV news hat': Laura Whitmore announces plans to leave MTV| date= 16 February 2015| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150216174738/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-leaving-mtv-news-statement/| archive-date= 16 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-the-hot-desk-new-itv2-show/| work= evoke.ie| title= Laura Whitmore is back in the hot seat after hanging up her MTV news hat| date= 17 February 2015| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150217120137/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-the-hot-desk-new-itv2-show/| archive-date= 17 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Her last bulletin with the station was recorded on 26 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goss.ie/2015/02/one-take-whitmore-records-her-final-mtv-news/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083440/http://www.goss.ie/2015/02/one-take-whitmore-records-her-final-mtv-news/ |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2016, Whitmore was announced as taking part in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', beginning September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/strictlycomedancing/entries/3619febd-d0d0-46b6-9ff3-b3c8fd93135a |title=BBC Blogs \u2013 Strictly Come Dancing \u2013 Laura Whitmore is the third celebrity to join the Strictly class of 2016! |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> She was partnered with Italian dancer [[Giovanni Pernice]] and was the sixth contestant to be voted out, on 5 November 2016 follow a dance off with eventual series champions [[Ore Oduba]] and [[Joanne Clifton]].\n\nIn 2018, Whitmore presented ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]'', a new reality series for [[ITV2]], alongside comedian Brennan Reece.<ref>https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/laura-whitmore-host-itv2s-survival-fittest</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2019, it was announced that Whitmore would host the sixth series of ITV2's ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]'' in 2020 after [[Caroline Flack]]'s exit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-17/caroline-flack-stand-down-host-of-upcoming-series-love-island-after-assault-charge/|title=Love Island host Caroline Flack standing down as host of upcoming series after assault charge|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv2-announces-laura-whitmore-will-host-season-6-love-island|title=ITV2 announces that Laura Whitmore will host season 6 of Love Island|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nIn August 2009, Whitmore launched a self-branded clothing range available at [[A Wear]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awear.com/Laura-Whitmore/icat/laura_whitmore_for_awear |title=Archived copy |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818010115/http://www.awear.com/Laura-Whitmore/icat/laura_whitmore_for_awear |archivedate=18 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Whitmore appeared on the September cover of ''[[FHM]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.fhm.com/covergirls/laura-whitmore|work=FHM | title= FHM Covergirls Laura Whitmore}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore is a spokeswoman for the [[Because I Am a Girl (campaign)|Because I Am a Girl]] charity clothing campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plan-uk.org/news/celebrities/laura-whitmore-clothing-range/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001044138/http://www.plan-uk.org/news/celebrities/laura-whitmore-clothing-range/ |archivedate= 1 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nLaura collaborated with [[Daisy London]] on a collection in October 2015. The collection was inspired by music and features the recurring shape of the [[plectrum]] throughout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefuss.co.uk/laura-whitmore-designs-jewellery-collection/|title=Laura Whitmore designs jewellery collection - The Fuss|date=13 November 2015|newspaper=The Fuss|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221235927/http://www.thefuss.co.uk/laura-whitmore-designs-jewellery-collection/|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.look.co.uk/fashion/laura-whitmore-daisy-london-party-62827|title=Go Inside The Hottest A-List Launch Party {{!}} Look|date=29 October 2015|newspaper=Look Magazine|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Whitmore launched Misstache for Movember, a campaign for women to support and raise awareness of the men's health charity.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-misstache-campaign-is-gathering-pace/| work= evoke.ie| title= Laura Whitmore Misstache campaign, is gathering pace. Now Roz Purcell and Vogue Williams have joined in| date= 9 November 2014| access-date= 27 January 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150224005715/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-misstache-campaign-is-gathering-pace/| archive-date= 24 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore appeared on [[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|''FHM''{{'s}} 100 Sexiest 2015]] list at number 37.<ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.fhm.com/100-sexiest-2015|work=FHM | title= FHM 100 Sexiest 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore features in the music video for \"[[Skip to the Good Bit]]\", a song by [[Rizzle Kicks]] and the music video for \"Mark My Words\" by [[The Coronas]]. In 2017, she played Cleo Morey alongside [[Shane Richie]], Bill Ward and Stephen Billington in the stage adaptation of the Peter James book ''Not Dead Enough''.\n\nWhitmore has had a weekly Sunday morning radio show on BBC Radio 5 Live since 2018. <ref>https://www.mcsaatchimerlin.com/talent/laura-whitmore</ref><ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/radio/2019-12-20/laura-whitmore-bbc-radio-5live/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| \n| ''[[Isle of Wight Festival]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| 2008\u20132015\n| ''[[MTV News|MTV News Ireland]]''\n| Presenter\n|-\n| 2011\u20132015\n| ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]''\n| Anchor\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2012\n| ''[[Beat TV]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[The Hit (Irish TV series)|The Hit]]'' (pilot)\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n|-\n| 2012\u20132016\n| ''[[The Hot Desk]]''\n|-\n| 2012\u20132016\n| ''[[BRIT Awards|The Brits Backstage]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Co-presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2014\n| ''[[11th Irish Film & Television Awards]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|Eurovision Song Contest Semi-Finals]]''\n|-\n| ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''\n| \"The Hub\" presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2016\n| ''[[BRIT Awards|The Brits Are Coming]]''\n| Presenter\n|-\n| ''[[V Festival|V Festival 2016]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\u2013\n|[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|''Love Island'']]\n|-\n|''[[Love Island: Aftersun]]''\n|}\n\n;Guest appearances\n{{div col }}\n*''[[Sunday Brunch]]'' (2012, 2015)\n*''[[The Xtra Factor (UK TV series)|The Xtra Factor]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Unzipped (TV series)|Unzipped]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2012, 2014)\n*''[[Britain's Got More Talent]]'' (2012, 2013, 2016, 2018)\n*''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Sweat the Small Stuff]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Fake Reaction]]'' (2013, 2014)\n*''[[Sunday Side Up]]'' (2013)\n*''[[A League of Their Own (UK game show)|A League of Their Own]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Virtually Famous]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Celebrity Squares]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Alan Carr's New Year Specstacular]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Irish TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://laurawhitmore.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|3189084}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitmore, Laura}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Griffith College]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bray, County Wicklow]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 television presenters]]\n[[Category:Television presenters from the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Irish presenter and actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laura Whitmore\n| image              = Jaguar XE - Arrival in London (15185880955) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Whitmore in 2014\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1985|05|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| nationality        = Irish\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Presenter|actress}}\n| years_active       = 2008\u2013present\n| education          = [[Dublin City University]]\n| partner            = [[Iain Stirling]]\n| website            = {{URL|http://laurawhitmore.com}}\n}}\n'''Laura Whitmore''' (born 4 May 1985)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://capitalfm.com/news/celebrity/laura-whitmore-tv-host-boyfriend-iain-stirling/|title=Who Is Laura Whitmore? Meet New Winter Love Island Host Dating Iain I Stirling|date=20 December 2019|work=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital]]}}</ref> is an Irish presenter and actress, known for presenting ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]'' and ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]''. In January 2020, Whitmore began presenting ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]'' and its spinoff series, ''[[Love Island: Aftersun]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nLaura Whitmore was born in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>https://twitter.com/thewhitmore/status/1172941403074310145</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/independent-woman/celebrity-news-gossip/laura-whitmore-i-cant-stand-still-not-for-a-second-3081169.html|title=Laura Whitmore: I can't stand still, not for a second |accessdate=28 August 2012|newspaper=The Irish Independent|date=15 April 2012}}</ref> She has two half brothers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rodgers|first=Kathryn|title=Babe Laura Whitmore moves in with Coronas star|url=http://www.clickonline.com/gossip/babe-laura-whitmore-moves-in-with-coronas-star/6712/|accessdate=28 August 2012|newspaper=Irish Tatler|date=14 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619015109/http://www.clickonline.com/gossip/babe-laura-whitmore-moves-in-with-coronas-star/6712|archivedate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Whitmore attended Loreto Bray, where she was awarded Culture Student of the Year upon graduating, before attending [[Dublin City University]] where she studied journalism, including a year studying abroad at [[Boston University]] in the United States. In 2003, Whitmore was a contestant in a modelling talent search on RT\u00c9's ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish talk show)|The Late Late Show]]'' with [[Pat Kenny]], reaching the final 15 of the competition.<ref>https://www.her.ie/entertainment/laura-whitmore-unrecognisable-photo-modelling-days-374250</ref>\nShe lives in [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], north London, as of 2018.<ref>https://irishtimes.com/life-and-style/home-and-property/interiors/at-home-with-laura-whitmore-i-love-my-records-most-1.3078220{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Television===\nIn April 2008, [[MTV Networks Europe]] launched a campaign ''Pick Me MTV''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/laura-whitmore |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831082708/http://www.fhm.com/girls/covergirls/laura-whitmore |archivedate=31 August 2009 }}</ref> where Whitmore battled it out against other contestants to become the face of [[MTV News]] in [[MTV Europe]]. Between 2008 and 2015, she hosted news bulletins for MTV in Ireland, the UK and pan-European MTV channels. She was regularly seen on MTV News hosting special events in Ireland and elsewhere in Europe.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/fashion/2008/1125/whitmorel.html \"My Style with Laura Whitmore\"]. Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann, 25 November 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614112652/http://www.rte.ie/fashion/2008/1125/whitmorel.html |date=14 June 2010 }}</ref> \n\nFor 5 series from 2011, Whitmore hosted ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]'' on [[ITV2]] airing immediately after ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!]]'' .<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s100/im-a-celebrity-uk/news/a348407/im-a-celebrity-return-date-confirmed-by-itv.html |title='I'm A Celebrity' return date confirmed by ITV |work=[[Digital Spy]] |first=Alex |last=Fletcher |date=31 October 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> Whitmore announced on 14 April 2016 that she had decided to leave the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker |first=Danny |url=http://mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/im-celebrity-presenter-laura-whitmore-7758971 |title=I'm A Celebrity presenter Laura Whitmore QUITS jungle spin-off after five years saying it was a '&#39;tough decision'&#39; \u2013 Mirror Online |website=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, Whitmore appeared on [[Miriam O'Callaghan (media personality)|Miriam O'Callaghan]]'s show ''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' after carrying the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] torch.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0713/thesaturdaynightshow.html |title=Laura Whitmore joins Miriam on Saturday |work=RT\u00c9 Ten |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715043314/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0713/thesaturdaynightshow.html |archivedate=15 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA [[pilot episode]] of songwriting-based talent show ''[[The Hit (Irish TV series)|The Hit]]'' aired in September 2012 on [[RT\u00c9 Two]], hosted by Whitmore. On 15 March 2013, RT\u00c9 announced that the show had been ordered for a full series which was broadcast in the summer, but Whitmore would not host due to conflicting schedule in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0315/444025-thehit/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107174715/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2013/0315/444025-thehit/ |archivedate= 7 January 2014 }}</ref> [[Aidan Power]] and [[Nicky Byrne]] presented the full series.\n\nIn April 2014, Whitmore co-hosted the ''[[11th Irish Film & Television Awards]]'' with [[Simon Delaney]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/simon-delaney-laura-whitmore-iftas-host-2014/| work= evoke.ie| title= Red carpet ready! Laura Whitmore confirmed to host the IFTA Awards with Simon Delaney| date= 13 March 2014| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121842/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/simon-delaney-laura-whitmore-iftas-host-2014/| archive-date= 17 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-says-she-cant-wait-to-co-host-the-iftas/| work=  evoke.ie| title=  Laura Whitmore talks to EVOKE.ie at the VOICE and says she can't wait to co-host the IFTAs with actor Simon Delaney| date=  23 March 2014| access-date=  17 February 2015| archive-url=  https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121327/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-says-she-cant-wait-to-co-host-the-iftas/| archive-date=  17 February 2015| url-status=  dead| df=  dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/you-live-and-learn-why-laura-whitmore-wont-dwell-on-iftas-and-the-technical-hitches-that-beset-the-awards-show/| work=  evoke.ie| title=  'You live and learn' \u2013 Why Laura Whitmore won't dwell on IFTAs and the technical hitches that beset the awards show| date=  5 May 2014| access-date=  17 February 2015| archive-url=  https://web.archive.org/web/20150217120449/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/you-live-and-learn-why-laura-whitmore-wont-dwell-on-iftas-and-the-technical-hitches-that-beset-the-awards-show/| archive-date=  17 February 2015| url-status=  dead| df=  dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Whitmore joined the [[United Kingdom in the Eurovision Song Contest|BBC Eurovision]] team as a commentator for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014]] semi-finals in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark alongside [[Scott Mills]] on [[BBC Three]]. She replaced [[Ana Matronic]] in the role,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/laura-adds-more-irish-sparkle-to-bbcs-eurovision-song-show-30157711.html|title=Laura adds more Irish sparkle to BBC's eurovision song show|publisher=Herald.ie|date=5 April 2014|accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref> but did not return in 2015. In 2014, she was an occasional presenter of \"The Hub\" section on ITV's ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''.\n\nOn 24 October 2014, Whitmore appeared in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night]]'' to raise awareness of testicular cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4043842/fullcredits/|title=The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night (2014 TV Movie) : Full Cast & Crew|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Whitmore announced that she was leaving MTV News after seven years presenting on the TV Channel, but would continue to present irregular segments and specials.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-leaving-mtv-news-statement/| work= evoke.ie| title= 'It's time to hang up my MTV news hat': Laura Whitmore announces plans to leave MTV| date= 16 February 2015| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150216174738/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-leaving-mtv-news-statement/| archive-date= 16 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-the-hot-desk-new-itv2-show/| work= evoke.ie| title= Laura Whitmore is back in the hot seat after hanging up her MTV news hat| date= 17 February 2015| access-date= 17 February 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150217120137/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-the-hot-desk-new-itv2-show/| archive-date= 17 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Her last bulletin with the station was recorded on 26 February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goss.ie/2015/02/one-take-whitmore-records-her-final-mtv-news/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083440/http://www.goss.ie/2015/02/one-take-whitmore-records-her-final-mtv-news/ |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2016, Whitmore was announced as taking part in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 14)|fourteenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', beginning September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/strictlycomedancing/entries/3619febd-d0d0-46b6-9ff3-b3c8fd93135a |title=BBC Blogs \u2013 Strictly Come Dancing \u2013 Laura Whitmore is the third celebrity to join the Strictly class of 2016! |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> She was partnered with Italian dancer [[Giovanni Pernice]] and was the sixth contestant to be voted out, on 5 November 2016 follow a dance off with eventual series champions [[Ore Oduba]] and [[Joanne Clifton]].\n\nIn 2018, Whitmore presented ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]'', a new reality series for [[ITV2]], alongside comedian Brennan Reece.<ref>https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/laura-whitmore-host-itv2s-survival-fittest</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2019, it was announced that Whitmore would host the sixth series of ITV2's ''[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]]'' in 2020 after [[Caroline Flack]]'s exit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-12-17/caroline-flack-stand-down-host-of-upcoming-series-love-island-after-assault-charge/|title=Love Island host Caroline Flack standing down as host of upcoming series after assault charge|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv2-announces-laura-whitmore-will-host-season-6-love-island|title=ITV2 announces that Laura Whitmore will host season 6 of Love Island|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nIn August 2009, Whitmore launched a self-branded clothing range available at [[A Wear]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awear.com/Laura-Whitmore/icat/laura_whitmore_for_awear |title=Archived copy |accessdate=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818010115/http://www.awear.com/Laura-Whitmore/icat/laura_whitmore_for_awear |archivedate=18 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Whitmore appeared on the September cover of ''[[FHM]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.fhm.com/covergirls/laura-whitmore|work=FHM | title= FHM Covergirls Laura Whitmore}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore is a spokeswoman for the [[Because I Am a Girl (campaign)|Because I Am a Girl]] charity clothing campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plan-uk.org/news/celebrities/laura-whitmore-clothing-range/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001044138/http://www.plan-uk.org/news/celebrities/laura-whitmore-clothing-range/ |archivedate= 1 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nLaura collaborated with [[Daisy London]] on a collection in October 2015. The collection was inspired by music and features the recurring shape of the [[plectrum]] throughout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefuss.co.uk/laura-whitmore-designs-jewellery-collection/|title=Laura Whitmore designs jewellery collection - The Fuss|date=13 November 2015|newspaper=The Fuss|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221235927/http://www.thefuss.co.uk/laura-whitmore-designs-jewellery-collection/|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.look.co.uk/fashion/laura-whitmore-daisy-london-party-62827|title=Go Inside The Hottest A-List Launch Party {{!}} Look|date=29 October 2015|newspaper=Look Magazine|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Whitmore launched Misstache for Movember, a campaign for women to support and raise awareness of the men's health charity.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-misstache-campaign-is-gathering-pace/| work= evoke.ie| title= Laura Whitmore Misstache campaign, is gathering pace. Now Roz Purcell and Vogue Williams have joined in| date= 9 November 2014| access-date= 27 January 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150224005715/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/laura-whitmore-misstache-campaign-is-gathering-pace/| archive-date= 24 February 2015| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore appeared on [[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|''FHM''{{'s}} 100 Sexiest 2015]] list at number 37.<ref>{{cite news| url=  http://www.fhm.com/100-sexiest-2015|work=FHM | title= FHM 100 Sexiest 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhitmore features in the music video for \"[[Skip to the Good Bit]]\", a song by [[Rizzle Kicks]] and the music video for \"Mark My Words\" by [[The Coronas]]. In 2017, she played Cleo Morey alongside [[Shane Richie]], Bill Ward and Stephen Billington in the stage adaptation of the Peter James book ''Not Dead Enough''.\n\nWhitmore has had a weekly Sunday morning radio show on BBC Radio 5 Live since 2018. <ref>https://www.mcsaatchimerlin.com/talent/laura-whitmore</ref><ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/radio/2019-12-20/laura-whitmore-bbc-radio-5live/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| \n| ''[[Isle of Wight Festival]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| 2008\u20132015\n| ''[[MTV News|MTV News Ireland]]''\n| Presenter\n|-\n| 2011\u20132015\n| ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! NOW!]]''\n| Anchor\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2012\n| ''[[Beat TV]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[The Hit (Irish TV series)|The Hit]]'' (pilot)\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Presenter\n|-\n| 2012\u20132016\n| ''[[The Hot Desk]]''\n|-\n| 2012\u20132016\n| ''[[BRIT Awards|The Brits Backstage]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Co-presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2014\n| ''[[11th Irish Film & Television Awards]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|Eurovision Song Contest Semi-Finals]]''\n|-\n| ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]''\n| \"The Hub\" presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2016\n| ''[[BRIT Awards|The Brits Are Coming]]''\n| Presenter\n|-\n| ''[[V Festival|V Festival 2016]]''\n| Co-presenter\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''\n| Contestant\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Survival of the Fittest (TV series)|Survival of the Fittest]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Presenter\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\u2013\n|[[Love Island (2015 TV series)|''Love Island'']]\n|-\n|''[[Love Island: Aftersun]]''\n|}\n\n;Guest appearances\n{{div col }}\n*''[[Sunday Brunch]]'' (2012, 2015)\n*''[[The Xtra Factor (UK TV series)|The Xtra Factor]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Unzipped (TV series)|Unzipped]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Saturday Night with Miriam]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2012, 2014)\n*''[[Britain's Got More Talent]]'' (2012, 2013, 2016, 2018)\n*''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Sweat the Small Stuff]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Fake Reaction]]'' (2013, 2014)\n*''[[Sunday Side Up]]'' (2013)\n*''[[A League of Their Own (UK game show)|A League of Their Own]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Virtually Famous]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Celebrity Squares]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Alan Carr's New Year Specstacular]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Irish TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'' (2018)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://laurawhitmore.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|3189084}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitmore, Laura}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Griffith College]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bray, County Wicklow]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 television presenters]]\n[[Category:Television presenters from the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Nidamaya", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Whitmore"}
{"title_page": "Divine (rapper)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = File:Vivian-Fernandes-Divine.webp\n| caption          = Vivian Fernandes pictured in 2018\n| Name             = DIVINE\n| background       = solo_singer<!-- this is a required field, do not change or remove -->\n| birth_name       = Vivian Fernandes\n| birth_date       = 2 October 1990\n| birth_place      = [[Andheri]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| Genre            = [[Hip Hop]], [[Rap]]\n| Occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[Lyricist]], [[Actor]]\n| Label            = [[Universal Music India]], [[Mass Appeal Records]] India, Gully Gang Entertainment, [[Red Bull]], [[Puma (brand)|Puma]], [[Netflix]], [[Sony Music India]]\n| years_active     = 2010-present\n| associated_acts  = [[Naezy]], [[Nucleya]], Rohan Thapa, [[Gangis Khan]], Deep Jandu, [[Raja Kumari]], Dub Sharma, Phenom, Sez, Karan Kanchan\n| origin           = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n}}\n\n'''Vivian Fernandes''', better known by his stage name '''DIVINE''', is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[rapper]] from [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]. He started to gain popularity after the release of his song ''Yeh Mera Bombay.'' He broke through with the release of his song ''Mere Gully Mein'' featuring fellow Mumbai rapper [[Naezy]].\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early years ===\nDivine started his career as an underground rapper in 2011 after discovering Hip Hop on a T-shirt. A friend of his wore a shirt of [[50 Cent]]'s first album [[Get Rich or Die Tryin'|Get Rich Or Die Tryin']] at school. The same friend would give him his first MP3 CD with hip hop music on it which inspired him to start rapping in English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/ht-brunch-cover-story-what-makes-gully-boy-divine-the-coolest-voice-of-contemporary-indian-hip-hop/story-GRCBw3nO7eFIasAd2agzGM.html|title=HT Brunch cover story: What makes \u2018gully boy\u2019 Divine the coolest voice of contemporary Indian hip-hop|date=2019-07-06|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> He was part of the hip hop crew called ''Mumbai's Finest''. He often raps about his own life experiences, such as the life of the poor people in Mumbai and his upbringing with a single mother. He cites American rappers such as [[Nas]], [[Eminem]], [[Big L]], Gangis Khan and [[Rakim]] as his main inspirations.\n\n=== Rise to success ===\nFollowing the release of his song ''[[Yeh Mera Bombay]]'', Divine obtained the attention of [[Sony Music India]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://qz.com/india/1166165/hard-kaur-divine-prabh-deep-sofia-ashraf-the-year-when-indian-hip-hop-cemented-its-place-on-the-music-charts/ |title=2017: The year when Indian hip-hop cemented its place on the music charts |last=Karkare |first=Aakash |website=Quartz India |language=en |access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref> while performing at the Blue Frog Festival 2014 in Mumbai and shortly after signed a contract with them. The song later went on to win the ''Best Video of the Year'' award by Rolling Stone India in the same year. He released his breakout single ''Mere Gully Main'' featuring [[Naezy]] on 16 April 2015. The song went viral and many [[Bollywood]] celebrities shared it on social media.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Will Mumbai rapper Divine become JB Nagar's Slumdog Millionaire? |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/will-mumbai-rapper-divine-become-jb-nagars-slumdog-millionaire/17056190 |journal=Mid Day |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>  He collaborated with Indian DJ [[Nucleya]] on Nucleya's album ''Bass Rani'', which helped him gain even more popularity. The song won ''Best EDM track of the Year'' in the GIMA Awards in 2015.\n\nOn 24 March 2016, his debut solo single ''Jungli Sher'' released and it ruled the charts because of its raw depiction of the life of the poor in Mumbai. He took the song to the Breakfast Show ahead of BBC Asian Network Live on 29 April 2016. He appeared on the [[BBC Asian Network]] in the Charlie Sloth Show and was the first Hindi-speaking rapper to freestyle on the show and also the first to rap in Hindi with the name-giving host in attendance. He was also featured on Brapp TV.<ref>{{cite journal |title=This hip-hop artist, who grew up in the slums of Mumbai, is going to London to perform on a BBC Radio show |journal=DNA India |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-this-hip-hop-artist-who-grew-up-in-the-slums-of-Mumbai-is-going-to-London-to-perform-on-a-bbc-radio-show-2199538 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe again collaborated with Nucleya in another hit track, entitled ''Scene Kya Hai'' off Nucleya's album ''Raja Baja''. He was featured on ''Daru Daru'' with Deep Jandu and Gangis Khan, his first commercially oriented song, which came out on 10 January 2017. His next solo single ''Farak'' released on 16 February 2017 and topped the [[Indian pop|Indipop]] charts on iTunes India.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Mumbai Rapper Divine's Biographical Song Jungli Sher's Video Shot Completely On iPhones Is Taking Over The Internet |journal=IndiaTimes |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/meet-the-mumbai-ghetto-rapper-divine-whose-biographical-rap-song-jungli-sher-s-video-shot-completely-on-iphones-is-taking-over-the-internet-252241.html |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a feature on a record called ''City Slums'' by Indian-American rapper/singer/songwriter [[Raja Kumari]] in May 2017. The song crossed 2 million views on YouTube within 24 hours of its release.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn 2018, Divine terminated his contract with Sony Music India. He released a remix to [[Lil Pump]]'s [[Gucci Gang]] called ''Gully Gang'' independently on 18 January 2018. The song was perceived well by both critics and fans and helped him garner more attention. On 5 April 2018, he followed up with ''One Side'' produced by Byg Byrd. The video was produced by [[Red Bull]] Media House and came out on the rapper's own YouTube channel.\n\nHis next single ''Teesri Manzil'' earned him a copyright strike from [[Zee Music Company]] a few hours after its release and got deleted from his channel. It was eventually re-released on 14 December 2018 with some changes in the lyrics.\n\nHe released ''Junoon'', the intro to his upcoming first full-length album on 10 November 2018. The album's name, ''Kohinoor'', was announced on 13 February 2019 on Apple Music's Beats 1 radio show hosted by [[Ebro Darden]]. The album release was announced to be somewhen in April 2019 but as of 15 April 2019 there weren't any news on the album's release.\n\nIn July 2019, Divine released a documentary film about his career so far entitled ''Gully Life - The story of DIVINE''. It first aired on TV on channels such as the Discovery Channel and was released on Divine's YouTube Channel a week later.<ref>{{Citation|title=GULLY LIFE - The Story of DIVINE (Full Movie)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjmqRgIoHP8|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2019, Nas' [[Mass Appeal Records]] and Universal Music India launched Mass Appeal India and signed Divine. In an interview with Nas published on Mass Appeal India's YouTube Channel <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9a-UBaeTyFY |title=The DIVINE & Nas Interview |language=en}}</ref> and Universal Music India's Facebook Page<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/universalmusicindia/videos/2399279810320101/ |title=Universal Music India - Nas and Divine's interview |language=en}}</ref> on 20 August 2019, Nas revealed that Divine's debut album ''Kohinoor'' is set to release soon. It was released on 9 October 2019 and features all-new tracks recorded specifically for the album.\n\n=== Film contributions ===\nDivine made his [[Bollywood]] debut for the film [[Mukkabaaz]] with the song ''Paintra''. The track was another collaboration with Nucleya and came out on 1 December 2017. He collaborated with famous Indian music director and singer [[Amit Trivedi]] for the [[Irrfan Khan]] Starter film [[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]] on a song ''Badla'' which came out on 16 March 2018 via [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]. He also contributed to the soundtrack for [[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/saif-ali-khan-to-star-in-netflix-series-sacred-games/story-AjtxogMzZezeXq5hDvWOoJ.html |title=Saif Ali Khan to star in Netflix series Sacred Games |date=14 July 2017 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=11 October 2017 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment-news/tv-shows/sacred-games-first-look-intense-edge-seat-drama-awaits-viewers |title=Sacred Games First Look: An Intense Edge-Of-The-Seat Drama Awaits Viewers |website=BookMyShow |accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref> an [[India]]n [[Netflix]] Original Series. It features his song ''Jungli Sher'' as well ''Kaam 25'' produced by Indo-Canadian producer Phenom which was made specifically for the series. Its music video was released on 14 June 2018 on both Divine's and Netflix's YouTube channels with the version on Netflix featuring English subtitles (Listen to Jungli Sher<ref>{{cite web |title=Jungli Sher - DIVINE - Official Music Video - with Lyrics & English Translation |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Wsi7YTI2nY |publisher=Youtube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and Kaam 25<ref>{{cite web |title=Kaam 25: DIVINE {{!}} Sacred Games {{!}} Netflix |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATf05n5LBHQ |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> on YouTube).\n\nDivine most notably contributed to the soundtrack of the 2019 film [[Gully Boy]] by [[Zoya Akhtar]], a film which is inspired by the lives of Naezy and himself, with [[Ranveer Singh]] and [[Alia Bhatt]] in the lead roles. Divine and Naezy both helped as consultants to get an authentic representation of the [[Hip hop|Hip Hop culture]] for the film. Their song ''Mere Gully Mein'' was remade with Ranveer Singh rapping Naezy's lyrics as part of the film. Furthermore, Divine provided additional rap lyrics for Ranveer Singh's character and composed some of the songs for the original soundtrack. A promotional single featuring American artist [[Nas]] as well as Naezy, Divine and Ranveer Singh was released on [[JioSaavn]] shortly prior to the film's release.\n\n== Gully Gang Entertainment ==\nIn February 2019 he announced the founding of a new company, ''Gully Gang Entertainment'', a record label to recruit and produce Hip Hop talent in the Mumbai area.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/rapper-divine-announces-gully-gang-entertainment-to-record-recruit-and-produce-hip-hop-talent-2027353.html |title=Rapper Divine Announces Gully Gang Entertainment to Record, Recruit and Produce Hip Hop Talent |website=News18 |access-date=9 February 2019}}</ref> ' Gully Gang Cypher<ref>{{cite web |title=GULLY GANG CYPHER - Aavrutti, D'Evil, Shah Rule, Karan Kanchan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Am9XxIAc0HI |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>' released on 22 May 2019, is the first song under the label and it features the emerging rap quartet Aavrutti, hip-hop artists D\u2019Evil, Shah RuLe and music producer Karan Kanchan for the project<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/its-a-wrap/article26618326.ece |title=It\u2019s a wrap for BUDX |last=Tagat |first=Anurag |date=2019-03-23 |work=The Hindu |access-date=2019-07-03 |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewildcity.com/news/13177-divine-s-gully-gang-records-kicks-off-with-gully-gang-cypher |title=DIVINE\u2019s Gully Gang Records Kicks Off With \u2018Gully Gang Cypher\u2019 |website=www.thewildcity.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''Kohinoor LP (2019)\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Performed By\n!Written By\n!Produced By\n|-